&lt;p&gt;Last week I spoke at New Adventures conference in Nottingham. After the afternoon‚Äôs talks, Jeff Veen recorded a panel for his Presentable podcast with the four speakers from that afternoon. &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.relay.fm/presentable/80&#34;&gt;You can now listen to the podcast online&lt;/a&gt; (and I‚Äôm sure you can find it in your podcast apps too).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The other three speakers were Liz Jackson, Florence Okoye and Tatiana Mac and they made this panel a ‚Äúcareer‚Äù highlight for me. Being onstage with these brilliant people all speaking so clearly and taking no bullshit was epic. (Also three of the most worthwhile speakers I‚Äôve ever seen in both content and delivery, I cannot overstate this enough.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.relay.fm/presentable/30&#34;&gt;I was also on Jeff‚Äôs podcast a couple of years ago&lt;/a&gt;. It feels like forever ago now, and it was nice to meet Jeff (however briefly) in person in Nottingham.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/presentable-live-panel-at-new-adventures-conference/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòPresentable Live panel at New Adventures Conference‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When you visit this website, I don‚Äôt track you.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You might‚Äôve noticed in the footer of my site, I have a little link (to this post) that says ‚ÄúNo tracking.‚Äù This is 100% borrowed/inspired by &lt;a href=&#34;https://thefox.is&#34;&gt;the footer text on Karolina Szczur‚Äôs website&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For me, ‚Äúno tracking‚Äù is both a fact and a mission statement. I‚Äôm not a fan of tracking. I work on a &lt;a href=&#34;https://better.fyi&#34;&gt;tracker blocker&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/tags/privacy/&#34;&gt;been writing about privacy for the last six years&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&#34;https://noti.st/laurakalbag/Y4Q95l/8-unbelievable-things-you-never-knew-about-tracking&#34;&gt;give whole talks about the harms of tracking on the web&lt;/a&gt;. Our work at &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org&#34;&gt;Small Technology Foundation&lt;/a&gt; is all about advocating for and building small technology to protect personhood and democracy in the digital network age.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That means that you will not find any analytics, article limits or cookies on my site. You also won‚Äôt find any third-party scripts, content delivery networks or third-party fonts. I won‚Äôt let anyone else track you either.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My site is run with &lt;a href=&#34;https://sitejs.org&#34;&gt;Site.js&lt;/a&gt;. Site.js provides some stats about visits to my site, but nothing about its visitors. I know how many requests my site has had, it‚Äôs top three most popular requests (&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/rss/&#34;&gt;my RSS feeds&lt;/a&gt;), requested but missing pages, and referrers. It‚Äôs as much as I need to keep my site running smoothly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/i-dont-track-you/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòI don‚Äôt track you‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://ar.al/2020/01/13/apple-says-no-and-what-that-means-for-the-future-of-better-blocker-following-our-move-to-ireland/&#34;&gt;Aral has written a detailed blog post about the logistics of moving our app&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://better.fyi&#34;&gt;Better Blocker&lt;/a&gt;, to our Irish organisation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In brief: we have to re-publish the app under Small Technology Foundation, which means anyone who wants to get future updates to the app will have to buy it again. (Though the previous version of the app will still be able to receive updates to the blocking rules.) We will lose years of favourable reviews, high rankings in our category, and a feature on the Safari App Extensions page. It‚Äôs immensely frustrating, and we‚Äôve been trying to find a way around it for the last few months. But we can‚Äôt. Because we have to play by Apple‚Äôs rules. &lt;a href=&#34;https://ar.al/2020/01/13/apple-says-no-and-what-that-means-for-the-future-of-better-blocker-following-our-move-to-ireland/&#34;&gt;Read all of Aral‚Äôs post on his blog&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;blocking-rule-updates&#34;&gt;Blocking rule updates&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One of the features that makes Better unique is that we curate our own list of blocking rules. Our focus is on blocking trackers, and we do so based on &lt;a href=&#34;https://ind.ie/ethical-design&#34;&gt;our principles of ethical design&lt;/a&gt;. This means we don‚Äôt block non-tracking ads, and when people report sites that break with Better, or have trackers we‚Äôve not blocked yet, we can update our blocking rules accordingly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Doing this work takes time, and while Aral does most of the work on the apps, I do most of the work on the blocking rules. I investigate every tracker to work out what it‚Äôs doing (and what it might do with your personal data!), write the rules, and push the updated block list out to everyone who uses Better. We provide these updates for free, and for a one-off App Store payment, it‚Äôs a bargain.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://better.fyi/news/&#34;&gt;You can read about all our blocking rule updates on the Better news page&lt;/a&gt;. And if you do, you‚Äôll notice that the second half of 2019 was slow for me. I was ill a lot last year, and had to prioritise the work that was paying more of the bills. And I felt like a horrible failure to all the people who had bought the apps.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;blocking-rules-in-2020&#34;&gt;Blocking rules in 2020&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But 2020 is a new year, and I‚Äôm starting it feeling the best I have in ages. Aral and I have been discussing our options with Better, given that &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org&#34;&gt;we are also working on other, more long-term, plans to make our work sustainable&lt;/a&gt;. We really care about Better being the best it can be for the people who have bought the apps. With this in mind, we‚Äôre aiming for less frequent but more regular blocking rule updates. &lt;strong&gt;We aim to update the blocking rules every month&lt;/strong&gt;, running more mass inspections of sites to be more efficient in blocking the most prevalent trackers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;thank-you-to-our-supporters&#34;&gt;Thank you to our supporters&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Finally, &lt;strong&gt;thank you&lt;/strong&gt; to the folks who discovered our work through Better and went on to &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/fund-us/&#34;&gt;support us with regulation donations&lt;/a&gt;. For years we‚Äôve talked about making Better a subscription-based app, but the development work required has exceeded the potential benefits. Our patrons have effectively supported blocking rule updates for everybody else (alongside the rest of our work), and we really appreciate their generosity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/the-future-of-better-blocker/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòThe future of Better Blocker‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Over the last few days, we closed the Ind.ie forum. It had been a fun experiment for 4.5 years, but didn‚Äôt really fit our aims to create decentralised technology. We didn‚Äôt want to shun other big platforms in favour of creating our own big platform, it would defeat the point!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;looking-for-better-support&#34;&gt;Looking for Better support?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We‚Äôve tried to cover most topics in depth on &lt;a href=&#34;https://better.fyi/support/&#34;&gt;Better‚Äôs Support page&lt;/a&gt;, for anything other Better support questions, feel free to email us at &lt;a href=&#34;mailto:hello@small-tech.org&#34;&gt;hello@small-tech.org&lt;/a&gt;, or send us a message on our &lt;a href=&#34;https://mastodon.ind.ie/@better&#34;&gt;Mastodon&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/betterblocker&#34;&gt;Twitter&lt;/a&gt; accounts. (We‚Äôve kept these accounts going for continuity.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;anonymous-support-requests&#34;&gt;Anonymous support requests&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What about anonymous support requests for Better? A few people have used the forum to get anonymous support because they‚Äôd rather not use their personal email or social media accounts. Some people have asked me to look into porn and fetish sites to more effectively block trackers, others have their own reasons for wanting privacy. But the forum was actually less anonymous. Signing up for the forum already requires an email address. And as the admin for a Discourse forum, I could access people‚Äôs email addresses, IP addresses, and detailed logs of their activity. I can tell you that you can trust me with your information, but I‚Äôd rather not have it in the first place. For those wanting to contact us anonymously with support requests, I‚Äôd recommend getting a temporary email address. It‚Äôs as easy as setting up a forum account anyway.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;45-years-is-a-long-time-on-the-web&#34;&gt;4.5 years is a long time on the web&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Honestly, it‚Äôs also miraculous we didn‚Äôt close the forum sooner. Of around 4.1k posts, 24% were by me. Most often I was posting links to thought-provoking articles I‚Äôd read, which I now post here on my site on &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/lens&#34;&gt;my lens&lt;/a&gt;. Or information about our Better blocking rule updates, which were always posted on &lt;a href=&#34;https://better.fyi/news/&#34;&gt;the Better website&lt;/a&gt; first. Very few people used our forum for support, usually preferring to send us an email. The forum became just like another social media platform, but one that cost us 120 US dollars per month.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;im-a-little-bit-sad&#34;&gt;I‚Äôm a little bit sad&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While the Ind.ie forum was intended to be a multifunctional place for temporary content, I did like the idea of fostering a community. It‚Äôs why I started sharing the articles I read, and tried to direct people there to discuss topics in more depth than we could manage on character-limited social media. But one determined person does not a community make. I developed some familiarity with a few repeat forum visitors, and we had the occasional detailed thread. But it was not the nuanced, inclusive and supportive discussion I craved. Nothing was abusive (as moderator, I‚Äôd shut things down early if I anticipated chat heading in that direction) but people tend to bring their pet topics, axes to grind, and presumptions of how much knowledge a small woman could possibly possess. Of course &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/insecure/&#34;&gt;I‚Äôve bleated about my desire for connection with likedminded folks before&lt;/a&gt; and it seems it‚Äôll remain a frequent whinge for a while longer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;people-not-brands&#34;&gt;People, not brands&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Along with our other work, the forum has been part of a learning process around where our output should live. When &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/a-belated-introduction-to-small-technology-foundation/&#34;&gt;we set up Small Technology Foundation&lt;/a&gt;, we decided that the definition of Small Technology Foundation is the collection of both &lt;a href=&#34;https://ar.al&#34;&gt;Aral&lt;/a&gt; and my work. And therefore we‚Äôd mostly write and share on our sites and spaces, under our own names, then bring anything relevant to Small Technology Foundation together on the &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org&#34;&gt;Small Technology Foundation site&lt;/a&gt;. There was no point having five different Twitter accounts for the work of two people. In fact, it was ridiculous. We are just two people, not a startup, not a big brand. We certainly don‚Äôt need people harbouring brand-sized expectations for us. And, &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/introducing-lauras-lens/&#34;&gt;as I mentioned in my post introducing the Lens&lt;/a&gt;, we have different perspectives and voices. It‚Äôs nice for those voices to be shared in context, rather than delivered as if unified under a confused brand.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôll still drift around various communities looking for a comfortable home. I‚Äôm increasingly aware that community is found in people, not on a website. But those people still need the means to communicate safely and freely, so &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org&#34;&gt;we‚Äôll keep working on that&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;aside id=&#34;like-this&#34;&gt;
    &lt;h2&gt;Like this? Support my work!&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;If you find my work useful or valuable, please help me continue by &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/fund-us&#34;&gt;supporting our work at Small Technology Foundation&lt;/a&gt;. We are a tiny not-for-profit organisation working on everyday tools for everyday people designed to increase human welfare, not corporate profits.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;You can support us by &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/fund-us&#34;&gt;becoming a patron of our foundation&lt;/a&gt;, or just by giving my work a shout-out. It really means a lot to me ‚ù§Ô∏è&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/closing-the-ind.ie-forum/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòClosing the Ind.ie forum‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I wrote &lt;a href=&#34;https://24ways.org/2019/its-time-to-get-personal/&#34;&gt;an ode to personal websites&lt;/a&gt; for one of my faves, &lt;a href=&#34;https://24ways.org&#34;&gt;24ways&lt;/a&gt;. Featuring inspiring (and rights-respecting) websites from people whose work I love and respect. Also including a festive sprinkling of &lt;a href=&#34;https://sitejs.org&#34;&gt;Site.js&lt;/a&gt;, which is making my development life much easier.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I love the little festive summary they wrote for me:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúLaura Kalbag discusses the gift of personal data we give to Big Tech when we share information on its platforms, and how reviving ye olde personal website can be one way to stay in control of the content we share and the data we leak. Christmas is a time for giving, but know what you‚Äôre giving to whom.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://24ways.org/2019/its-time-to-get-personal/&#34;&gt;Read It‚Äôs Time to Get Personal on 24ways&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;aside id=&#34;like-this&#34;&gt;
    &lt;h2&gt;Like this? Support my work!&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;If you find my work useful or valuable, please help me continue by &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/fund-us&#34;&gt;supporting our work at Small Technology Foundation&lt;/a&gt;. We are a tiny not-for-profit organisation working on everyday tools for everyday people designed to increase human welfare, not corporate profits.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;You can support us by &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/fund-us&#34;&gt;becoming a patron of our foundation&lt;/a&gt;, or just by giving my work a shout-out. It really means a lot to me ‚ù§Ô∏è&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/its-time-to-get-personal-on-24ways/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòIt‚Äôs Time To Get Personal on 24ways‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;About a month ago, &lt;a href=&#34;https://ar.al&#34;&gt;Aral&lt;/a&gt; and I launched Small Technology Foundation. In the frenzied rush to get the site up, and general life chaos that has overwhelmed me since, I‚Äôd not managed to write about it until now.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;a-new-name&#34;&gt;A new name?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs important to say that, while Small Technology Foundation is a new name for our organisation, it‚Äôs a continuation of the work we were doing as &lt;a href=&#34;https://ind.ie&#34;&gt;Ind.ie&lt;/a&gt;. What started as Irish restrictions preventing us from using the same name as our UK organisation, ended up being an opportunity to find a name that is more descriptive of the work we do, and more memorable. (Not to mention that Ind.ie is pronounced as ‚ÄúIndustrial-dot-IE‚Äù by some screenreaders, which has always irritated me.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;what-is-small-technology&#34;&gt;What is small technology?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/about/#small-technology&#34;&gt;Small Technology&lt;/a&gt; are everyday tools for everyday people designed to increase human welfare, not corporate profits. The opposite of big tech. We‚Äôre on a mission to build tools that enable everyone of us to own and control our own place on the Internet.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;what-is-the-foundation&#34;&gt;What is the foundation?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Small Technology Foundation is just the two of us, &lt;a href=&#34;https://ar.al&#34;&gt;Aral&lt;/a&gt; and me. (And &lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/gigapup&#34;&gt;Osky&lt;/a&gt;.) The foundation is a collection of our work. We do most of our work together, but also have our own ways of working towards Small Technology Foundation‚Äôs goals. (For example, &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/book&#34;&gt;I wrote a book&lt;/a&gt; and do a lot of reading which makes up &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/lens&#34;&gt;my lens&lt;/a&gt;.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For a long time, I resisted calling myself co-founder, as it brings up visions of startup hustlers and growth obsessives. I was much happier calling myself a designer, and pretending that one day soon I‚Äôd be spending 90% of my time designing and building websites again. But, as anyone who runs a not-for-profit organisation knows, keeping even the tiniest organisation running smoothly requires a lot of admin. And as anyone who is trying to make change in this forsaken tech community knows, it requires a lot of energy, communication, and saying the same things over and over again in the hope that someone might listen.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So while I still cherish the few hours I can dedicate to making websites, the grownup title of Co-Founder better fits the variety in my work. (And maybe men in suits will no longer dismiss me at conferences! ‚Ä¶jk, of course they‚Äôll still ignore me.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;not-for-profit&#34;&gt;Not. for. profit.&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As with Ind.ie, Small Technology Foundation is a not-for-profit organisation. We‚Äôre not in this for the cash. (If you want to make money in the tech industry, you don‚Äôt challenge the status quo‚Ä¶) We only pay ourselves what we need to pay our bills and feed the dog.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We‚Äôve only existed to this point with the help of a few kind supporters, but we do have a &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/fund-us/#our-sustainability-not-growth-plan.&#34;&gt;plan for long-term sustainability&lt;/a&gt; If you‚Äôre a person with financial means, &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/fund-us/&#34;&gt;we‚Äôd appreciate your monetary support&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/fund-us/#other-ways-to-support-us&#34;&gt;we have other (not monetary) ways to support us listed on our ‚Äúfund us‚Äù page&lt;/a&gt;. If you‚Äôre glad we exist (we hear this a lot! we appreciate it!) please help us continue to exist.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/a-belated-introduction-to-small-technology-foundation/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòA belated introduction to Small Technology Foundation‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Over the last five years or so, I‚Äôve been sharing links to insightful articles with a critical view of technology. It started as &lt;a href=&#34;https://2017.ind.ie/blog/the-sticky-pocked-underbelly-of-the-web/&#34;&gt;Ind.ie‚Äôs weekly roundup email&lt;/a&gt;, but I found writing a long summary was taking me too long every week (I‚Äôm no journalist!) So the roundups evolved into &lt;a href=&#34;https://ind.ie/radar&#34;&gt;Ind.ie‚Äôs daily Radar&lt;/a&gt;, where I‚Äôd post daily links, quoting some of the best bits, which I‚Äôd also post to &lt;a href=&#34;http://mastodon.ind.ie/@indie&#34;&gt;@indie on Mastodon&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/indie&#34;&gt;@indie on Twitter&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;whats-mine-is-mine-and-whats-ours-is-his&#34;&gt;What‚Äôs mine is mine and what‚Äôs ours is his&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When we started &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org&#34;&gt;Small Technology Foundation&lt;/a&gt;, we decided these links needed &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/lens&#34;&gt;a new home&lt;/a&gt;. These links have always been &lt;em&gt;my&lt;/em&gt; view of what &lt;em&gt;I&lt;/em&gt; think is related to our work. That is not to say that &lt;a href=&#34;https://ar.al&#34;&gt;Aral&lt;/a&gt; disagrees with my perspective, but that both Ind.ie and Small Technology Foundation have always been a collection of mine and Aral‚Äôs work. That‚Äôs why we blog on our own sites and then share the relevant posts aggregated on the &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/news/&#34;&gt;Small Technology Foundation news&lt;/a&gt;. Thus it also makes sense for &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/lens&#34;&gt;the links I collect to live on my site&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But there‚Äôs another reason why me posting as myself is valuable. Unless we specifically say the work I do is done by me, my work is often attributed to Aral. It‚Äôs not Aral‚Äôs fault. He‚Äôs deliberate in attributing my work to me, and continually corrects people who attribute my work to him or our work to him alone. But sometimes even that is not enough. We‚Äôve even had people assuming he co-wrote &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/book&#34;&gt;my book&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A few months ago, we gave our first talk together. We thought it would be fun, getting to give a talk that embodied our combined perspectives and unified talks we‚Äôd been giving separately. It was a lovely conference with a focus on inclusivity with a reasonable mixture of speakers and attendees from different backgrounds. But it was the starkest example of how my work, and even my presence, are erased, despite being amongst a broadly progressive community.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We shared the talk as two halves. My half of the talk was strong and, while Aral has had a longer speaking career, combined we gave a really good talk (I didn‚Äôt let him down!) However afterwards, multiple speakers referred to ‚ÄúAral‚Äôs talk‚Äù in their talks. One then corrected himself, asking the audience to remind him of my name, and then continued to refer to ‚ÄúAral‚Äôs talk.‚Äù People flocked to Aral to invite him to speak at their events, they stopped him later to commend him on his talk. I don‚Äôt want to be ungrateful to the people who came to speak to me afterwards, and said lovely things about our talk, but they were a kind minority to those crowding Aral. It broke my heart a little bit.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Aral and I know we‚Äôre perceived and treated differently in the world. It might have something to do with my looking younger than I am, it might be because I‚Äôm often less confident. But it‚Äôs likely because I‚Äôm a woman. While what I face is nothing compared to those battling racism and ableism in the tech community, I get dealt a fair amount of crap from that community and (not just &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/notes/14/&#34;&gt;bad tweets&lt;/a&gt;.) We‚Äôre not going to fix systemic problems by being clearer in attributing my work to me, in fact we may just make my work easier to ignore as women‚Äôs work in the tech community so often is (along with the work of people of colour, and that of people with visible disabilities). But we can do this one thing to stop people attributing my work to somebody else.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(I know‚Ä¶ all this in a post about posting links. Trust me, this feels tedious to me too.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;my-lens-means-whats-important-to-me&#34;&gt;My lens means what‚Äôs important to me&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As I said, &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/lens&#34;&gt;the links on my lens&lt;/a&gt; are from my perspective. This means often I include articles that aren‚Äôt written from a technologist‚Äôs point of view and aren‚Äôt focused on design and development. The articles are usually more about politics, society and culture, and where technology fits in. That‚Äôs why we (well, Aral) came up with the name, ‚Äú&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/lens&#34;&gt;Laura‚Äôs Lens&lt;/a&gt;.‚Äù (I‚Äôm terrible at naming things.) This is a reading list of what I‚Äôm using to inform my work at Small Technology Foundation. These are pieces that help me understand topics, connect themes together and learn how to explain key issues. I limit it to one article daily (on weekdays), and I hope you find them as valuable as I do.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;like-the-lens-fund-us&#34;&gt;Like the lens? Fund us!&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Small Technology Foundation is a not-for-profit organisation. All the work I do is part of our effort to advocate for and build &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/#small-technology&#34;&gt;small technology&lt;/a&gt; to protect personhood and democracy in the digital network age. If you find my work at all valuable (and can afford to do so), I would really appreciate your financial support. &lt;a href=&#34;https://small-tech.org/fund-us/&#34;&gt;Our Small Technology funding page&lt;/a&gt; has more information on how you can donate to us, become a patron, and the work that is funded by our supporters.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/introducing-lauras-lens/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòIntroducing Laura‚Äôs Lens‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A few weeks ago, I chatted to James Jeffrey for a BBC article on &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-49694453&#34;&gt;Why much of the internet is closed off to blind people&lt;/a&gt;. In particular, I spoke to how easy it can be to make a website accessible, and why it should be part of our everyday practice as designers and developers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúIt&amp;rsquo;s not hard to do, it should just be part of best practice, not an additional line item, just like making sure a website loads quickly is,‚Äù says Laura Kalbag, a website designer and author of Accessibility for Everyone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúIt basically just involves HTML coding, which even a blogger can do. If it is a huge website, it might take some time, but the work itself is not complicated.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;She adds it is a myth that making a website accessible makes it ugly, there is no correlation - you can still have snazzy images and graphics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúWe treat disabled people as if they are different but that isn&amp;rsquo;t the case, as digital accessibility affects all of us,‚Äù says Ms Kalbag. ‚ÄúIf nothing else, you should see it in a selfish way, as one day you will probably need this type of accessibility.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-49694453&#34;&gt;Read the full article on the BBC website&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/why-much-of-the-internet-is-closed-off-to-blind-people/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòWhy much of the internet is closed off to blind people‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This summer/autumn, I‚Äôm speaking at conferences in Amsterdam, London and Edinburgh. This year I‚Äôve had mixed experiences with speaking, so I‚Äôm being picky about future talks. So I‚Äôm looking forward to the following‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;loupe&#34;&gt;Loupe&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Amsterdam, 15th August.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Next week I‚Äôll be in Amsterdam to give an introductory talk about accessible and inclusive design at &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.framer.com/loupe/&#34;&gt;Framer‚Äôs Loupe conference&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;state-of-the-browser&#34;&gt;State Of The Browser&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;London, 14th September.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In September, I‚Äôm reuniting with a bunch of old pals, and hoping to make new ones at &lt;a href=&#34;https://2019.stateofthebrowser.com&#34;&gt;London Web Standards‚Äô State Of The Browser 2019&lt;/a&gt;. I last spoke at this conference in 2013, and did one of my first ever talks at one of their meetups in 2012. It‚Äôs going to be a proper party.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;accessibility-scotland&#34;&gt;Accessibility Scotland&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Edinburgh, 25th October.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In October, I‚Äôll be back to Edinburgh for &lt;a href=&#34;https://accessibility.scot&#34;&gt;Accessibility Scotland&lt;/a&gt;. I‚Äôm really looking forward to this event, as the theme is ‚Äúaccessibility and ethics‚Äù (right up my street!) and so far the lineup is fabulous.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/where-im-speaking-in-summer/autumn-2019/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòWhere I‚Äôm speaking in Summer/Autumn 2019‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I almost forgot to share photos of the gorgeous &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/this-one-weird-trick-tells-us-everything-about-you&#34;&gt;printed Smashing Magazine&lt;/a&gt;! Getting all this into 2000 words was a challenge, but I‚Äôm happy with the result.&lt;/p&gt;
