&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Article: &lt;a href=&#34;https://stephaniewalter.design/blog/tips-create-accessible-color-palette/&#34;&gt;Tips to Create an Accessible and Contrasted Color Palette&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/dangerous-data-and-understanding-privilege/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòDangerous data and understanding privilege‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the last year, I‚Äôve had two notably bad experiences with mic fittings when speaking at conferences. Nowadays most events have a Code of Conduct, but I‚Äôve found them to be largely unenforced, with some of the worst conduct coming from organisers or people working for the event.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#how-to-fit-a-microphone-to-a-person-without-making-them-feel-uncomfortable&#34;&gt;Skip the background, get straight to how to fit a microphone to a person without making them feel uncomfortable&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A couple of weeks ago, I posted on &lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/laurakalbag/status/1095258739777646598&#34;&gt;Twitter&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;https://mastodon.laurakalbag.com/web/statuses/101578507803428637&#34;&gt;Mastodon&lt;/a&gt; looking for advice for tech teams on how to fit a mic and behave appropriately:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Recently I had another bad experience with a person fitting my mic at a conf where I was speaking. Can anyone recommend good resources on appropriate behaviour for conf tech teams?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(If I‚Äôm going to blog about it, I‚Äôd like to link to legit advice from people who know their stuff!)‚Ä¨&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unfortunately, without explicit descriptions of what happened, a few people made their own assumptions. Perhaps I don‚Äôt know how wireless microphones work and how they should be fitted. Or I am a diva who refuses to fit a microphone to herself. Or I don‚Äôt know how to use verbal and physical language to deter men from touching me inappropriately. Let me describe the two particular scenarios that happened to me.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Scenario one was a panel where I needed a lapel mic (small mic attached to a clip) fitted to the chest of my shirt. It‚Äôs easy to clip a lapel mic to a shirt because there are gaps between buttons where you can clip the mic, and the buttons ensure it doesn‚Äôt ride up or slip down. Then you have to find a place to clip/hide the wireless receiver (often referred to as a ‚Äòmic pack‚Äô) and all the cable that runs between the mic and the receiver. It‚Äôs usually easiest to attach the mic pack to a waistband or belt or put it a back pocket. Then you can hide the cable under your clothes so it doesn‚Äôt look messy or get caught or tangled while you‚Äôre speaking.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;On this occasion, the tech person clipped the lapel mic to my shirt, then put their hand down the inside of my shirt to feed the mic pack and cable to the back of my body.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Scenario two was a talk where I needed a head mic, a small mic that sits alongside the face, attached with hooks over the ears and around the back of the head. As with the lapel mic, you have to attach the mic pack to something and hide the cables. I was wearing a dress with tights underneath, and I knew this meant it was slightly trickier to attach the mic pack. Still, I was prepared to fit it to the waistband at the back of my tights.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I discussed the fitting with the tech person who promptly lifted the back of my dress to start putting the mic pack on the waistband of my tights. They also did the same thing again when I went to remove the mic after my talk.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;On both occasions I assured the tech person I knew how to fit a microphone, and was willing to put the microphone where they needed, based on their advice. I‚Äôve used microphones enough times to know the basics, but also understand that they‚Äôre the experts and know what will produce the best sound quality. Both times, when I was uncomfortable with the way they touched me, I quickly moved, taking the mic pack away from them, to do it myself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I don‚Äôt think either of these people had ulterior motives, they weren‚Äôt trying to harass me. But both incidents made me incredibly uncomfortable. I don‚Äôt expect to be touched, or to have my clothes moved or removed, by a stranger without my permission or at least prior warning.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It would be easy to consider me overly sensitive or insecure to react in such a way in these scenarios. But honestly, having strangers touch you like this can really throw you, especially if you‚Äôre already feeling tense and unsure of yourself. I don‚Äôt want to be touched up by a stranger before waltzing on stage! Both times I didn‚Äôt make a fuss (though I had every right to do so) but instead told the organisers later. Mostly because I was about to give a talk and take part in a panel. I was already nervous and my mind was occupied with doing the best job I could for the event. I didn‚Äôt need to be worrying about what just happened on top of everything else. I‚Äôm usually nervous and awkward for the first few minutes of an event, it takes me time to warm up and be comfortable in front of people. These experiences amplified that tense nervousness and the feeling I was not in control.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And I didn‚Äôt need to be made to feel this way. It wasn‚Äôt appropriate behaviour that considered my feelings. These were both events staffed with professional tech teams. They weren‚Äôt even volunteers or people who hadn‚Äôt fitted microphones before. And importantly, this doesn‚Äôt happen at every event where I speak. For better or worse, I‚Äôm the kind of conflict-averse person that‚Äôll put up with a lot of slights before I comment. I can imagine experiences like this could completely alienate women and other marginalised people who are new to speaking.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We need to conduct ourselves in an inclusive and considerate manner to attract (and not deter!) more speakers to spaces where their voices are desperately needed.&lt;/p&gt;

