&lt;h2 id=&#34;how-to-fit-a-microphone-to-a-person-without-making-them-feel-uncomfortable&#34;&gt;How to fit a microphone to a person without making them feel uncomfortable&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I asked for advice on Twitter and Mastodon because couldn‚Äôt find any useful or relevant guidance on how to fit a microphone to a person without making them feel uncomfortable. Is this because it‚Äôs considered common sense? Is it because professionals have their own policies? I‚Äôve no idea, but given that many conference organisers are folks who don‚Äôt have a background in event management, maybe some basic guidance would be useful.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/amarkon88&#34;&gt;Adam Markon&lt;/a&gt; kindly shared his protocol when he used to work in TV production for sports:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;demonstrate on ourselves where we need everything to go and explain how the mic itself works if they don‚Äôt know&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ask if they‚Äôre comfortable doing it themselves or if they need help with any steps&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;if they need help at any point be very clear about where your hands will be and what you‚Äôre trying to do&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This really covers all the basics. Personally I don‚Äôt require someone of the same gender to fit my microphone (understandably this would make some people feel more comfortable.) I‚Äôm even fine with being touched by a person fitting a microphone, just as long as they ask first and warn me what they‚Äôre doing to do. &lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/akareilly&#34;&gt;Karen Reilly&lt;/a&gt; recommended &lt;a href=&#34;https://forums.prosoundweb.com/index.php?topic=149960.0&#34;&gt;this interesting forum thread on etiquette for fitting mics&lt;/a&gt;. There‚Äôs so much valuable advice in there too (along with some odd suggestions like wearing gloves!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you‚Äôre a conference organiser reading this, I‚Äôd really appreciate you briefing your tech team on fitting microphones. Even if they‚Äôre a professional team where you assume they know what they‚Äôre doing. I‚Äôd consider it a vital part of enforcing a code of conduct, and a way to show you really care about the experience of your speakers. Little things make a difference.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Thanks to &lt;a href=&#34;https://ar.al&#34;&gt;Aral&lt;/a&gt; for his proof-reading eye.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/mic-issues/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòMic Issues‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm not committing to a weekly anything! Incidentally, here‚Äôs the best bookmarks I saved in Week 9, 2019.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;silicon-valley-darkness&#34;&gt;Silicon Valley Darkness&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you used to read my &lt;a href=&#34;https://ind.ie/news&#34;&gt;Ind.ie roundups&lt;/a&gt; or you follow &lt;a href=&#34;https://mastodon.ind.ie/@indie&#34;&gt;@indie@mastodon.ind.ie on Mastodon&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/indie&#34;&gt;@indie on Twitter&lt;/a&gt; (I post lots of links there!), you‚Äôll know I‚Äôve always got something to populate this category. I am not your breathless startup cheerleader. Links this week feature lights being shone on the darkness of Facebook and Google, and UK and EU regulators trying (and often failing) to rein in the Silicon Valley monsters.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;you-give-apps-sensitive-personal-information-then-they-tell-facebook&#34;&gt;You Give Apps Sensitive Personal Information. Then They Tell Facebook.&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By Sam Schechner and Mark Secada on The Wall Street Journal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúThe social-media giant collects intensely personal information from many popular smartphone apps just seconds after users enter it, even if the user has no connection to Facebook‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Article: &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.wsj.com/articles/you-give-apps-sensitive-personal-information-then-they-tell-facebook-11550851636&#34;&gt;You Give Apps Sensitive Personal Information. Then They Tell Facebook.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;nest-secure-had-a-secret-microphone-can-now-be-a-google-assistant&#34;&gt;Nest Secure had a secret microphone, can now be a Google Assistant&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By Ms. Smith on CSO&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúIf your IoT device secretly contained a microphone, which was previously undocumented, would you be happy when the device maker announced an over-the-air update that can enable the microphone for virtual assistant voice functionality? That‚Äôs what happened with the security alarm system Nest Secure.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Article: &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.csoonline.com/article/3336227/security/nest-secure-had-a-secret-microphone-can-now-be-a-google-assistant.html&#34;&gt;Nest Secure had a secret microphone, can now be a Google Assistant&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;facebook-labelled-digital-gangsters-by-report-on-fake-news&#34;&gt;Facebook labelled &amp;lsquo;digital gangsters&amp;rsquo; by report on fake news&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By David Pegg on The Guardian&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Labour moved quickly to endorse the committee‚Äôs findings, with the party‚Äôs deputy leader, Tom Watson, announcing: ‚ÄúLabour agrees with the committee‚Äôs ultimate conclusion ‚Äì the era of self-regulation for tech companies must end immediately.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúWe need new independent regulation with a tough powers and sanctions regime to curb the worst excesses of surveillance capitalism and the forces trying to use technology to subvert our democracy.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Article: &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/feb/18/facebook-fake-news-investigation-report-regulation-privacy-law-dcms&#34;&gt;Facebook labelled &amp;lsquo;digital gangsters&amp;rsquo; by report on fake news&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;why-a-focus-on-fake-news-and-facebook-misses-the-internets-real-problems---and-solutions&#34;&gt;Why a focus on ‚Äúfake news‚Äù and Facebook misses the internet‚Äôs real problems - and solutions&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By Jennifer Cobbe on Open Democracy&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúThe biggest oversight‚Ä¶ is in diagnosing disinformation as essentially a problem with Facebook, rather than a systemic issue emerging in part from the pollution of online spaces by the business model that Facebook shares with others: the surveillance and modification of human behaviour for profit.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Article: &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.opendemocracy.net/uk/jennifer-cobbe/why-focus-on-fake-news-and-facebook-misses-internets-real-problems-and-solutions&#34;&gt;Why a focus on ‚Äúfake news‚Äù and Facebook misses the internet‚Äôs real problems - and solutions&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;even-the-iab-warned-adtech-risks-eu-privacy-rules&#34;&gt;Even the IAB warned adtech risks EU privacy rules&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By Natasha Lomas on Techcrunch&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúThe IAB is certainly seeking to deploy pro-privacy arguments to try to dilute Europeans‚Äô privacy rights.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Article: &lt;a href=&#34;https://techcrunch.com/2019/02/21/even-the-iab-warned-adtech-risks-eu-privacy-rules/&#34;&gt;Even the IAB warned adtech risks EU privacy rules&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;the-secret-lives-of-facebook-moderators-in-america&#34;&gt;The secret lives of Facebook moderators in America&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By Casey Newton on The Verge&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúThat people don‚Äôt know there are human beings doing this work is, of course, by design. Facebook would rather talk about its advancements in artificial intelligence, and dangle the prospect that its reliance on human moderators will decline over time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But given the limits of the technology, and the infinite varieties of human speech, such a day appears to be very far away. In the meantime, the call center model of content moderation is taking an ugly toll on many of its workers.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Article: &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/25/18229714/cognizant-facebook-content-moderator-interviews-trauma-working-conditions-arizona&#34;&gt;The secret lives of Facebook moderators in America&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;css-for-good-and-evil&#34;&gt;CSS for good and evil&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I like the trajectory of this post, looking at how CSS is employed to thwart blocking technologies, then to how the same CSS could be used in a positive manner, all wrapped in accessibility concerns.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;spanlspanspanespanspantspanspantspanspanespanspanrspanspansspan&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;L&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;e&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;t&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;t&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;e&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;r&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;s&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By Chris Coyier on CSS Tricks.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄòIt just feels so rude, doesn&amp;rsquo;t it? Like a user specifically installs technology onto their computer in order to exert some control over what they allow onto their computers and into their eyeballs. And they are saying, ‚ÄúNo, we do not respect that choice. We are going to fight your technology with our technology and force feed this stuff onto your computer and your eyeballs.‚Äù Doesn&amp;rsquo;t sit right.‚Äô&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Article: &lt;a href=&#34;https://css-tricks.com/spanl-spanspane-spanspant-spanspant-spanspane-spanspanr-spanspans-span/&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;L&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;e&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;t&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;t&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;e&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;r&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;s&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;being-a-woman&#34;&gt;Being a woman&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Over the last decade I‚Äôve gone from being wilfully ignorant of how women are treated to being frustrated by it on a daily basis. The last week gave me horror and horrified delight from two bookmarks.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;the-deadly-truth-about-a-world-built-for-men--from-stab-vests-to-car-crashes&#34;&gt;The deadly truth about a world built for men ‚Äì from stab vests to car crashes&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By Caroline Criado-Perez on The Guardian.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúCrash-test dummies based on the ‚Äòaverage‚Äô male are just one example of design that forgets about women ‚Äì and puts lives at risk‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Article: &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2019/feb/23/truth-world-built-for-men-car-crashes&#34;&gt;The deadly truth about a world built for men ‚Äì from stab vests to car crashes&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;the-reply-guy-constitution&#34;&gt;The Reply Guy Constitution&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By Emlyn Crenshaw on McSweeney‚Äôs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúSection 2 ‚Äì The Comment. Our replies to all tweets shall fall into one of the following categories: unsolicited advice, explanation, contrarian comment, request for research to be done on Our behalf, improvement upon the joke, and/or sucketh upping. When We cannot think of a proper reply to the tweet in question, a .gif of minimal relevance shall suffice. Above all, no woman shall be excluded from Our familiar and chummy tone.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Funny: &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.mcsweeneys.net/articles/the-reply-guy-constitution&#34;&gt;The Reply Guy Constitution&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;light-relief&#34;&gt;Light relief&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Ending on something nice‚Ä¶ ten years ago, my pal and then-flatmate Scott Coello made this animation for a dog I loved. His work on it features heavily in my memory of our last year at university, and likely includes some of my junk mail. The animation is so good, adorable, and really stands the test of time.&lt;/p&gt;
