&lt;p&gt;Video: &lt;a href=&#34;https://vimeo.com/3319096&#34;&gt;She Farted And Created The World&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/silicon-valley-darkness-and-being-a-woman/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòSilicon Valley Darkness and Being a Woman‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Last Friday afternoon, I had a lovely chat with Liz Elcoate about ethics, inclusivity and accessibility in design and branding. That chat is now available as Episode 4 of Liz‚Äôs podcast, &lt;a href=&#34;http://theelasticbrand.com/episode/ep-4-laura-kalbag/&#34;&gt;The Elastic Brand&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Too often, designers feel like they‚Äôre operating on the whims of their clients or employers, implementing design in a superficial manner, not able to have an impact. We discuss how that doesn‚Äôt have to be the case, and how we hope our insecurities are making us better people and designers!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://theelasticbrand.com/episode/ep-4-laura-kalbag/&#34;&gt;Listen to Episode 4 of The Elastic Brand podcast on the podcast website&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/elastic-brand-podcast/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòElastic Brand podcast‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We are seeing more and more organisations starting to talk about ethical design. Unfortunately I suspect this has less to do with caring about the impact of unethical design on society, democracy and the environment, and more to do with organisations attempting to distance themselves from similar businesses who are finding it impossible to continue to disguise their toxicity.&lt;/p&gt;
