&lt;p&gt;A few weeks ago I gave a workshop in New Zealand about designing inclusive content and accessible design. Afterwards, I was asked for recommended reading on accessible animation. These are a bunch of bookmarks I‚Äôve stored up, and what I‚Äôd recommend to get started on designing and building animations in an inclusive way:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;books&#34;&gt;Books&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://rosenfeldmedia.com/books/designing-interface-animation/&#34;&gt;Designing Interface Animation&lt;/a&gt; by Val Head.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://abookapart.com/products/animation-at-work&#34;&gt;Animation At Work&lt;/a&gt; by Rachel Nabors.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;articles&#34;&gt;Articles&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://source.opennews.org/articles/motion-sick/&#34;&gt;Your Interactive Makes Me Sick&lt;/a&gt; by Eileen Webb.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://alistapart.com/article/patterns-and-purpose&#34;&gt;Patterns and Purpose, an Excerpt from Animation at Work&lt;/a&gt; by Rachel Nabors.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://alistapart.com/article/designing-safer-web-animation-for-motion-sensitivity&#34;&gt;Designing Safer Web Animation For Motion Sensitivity&lt;/a&gt; by Val Head.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://alistapart.com/article/designing-interface-animation-interview-with-val-head&#34;&gt;Designing Interface Animation: an Interview with Val Head&lt;/a&gt; by Mica McPheeters and Caren Litherland.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://css-tricks.com/introduction-reduced-motion-media-query/&#34;&gt;An Introduction to the Reduced Motion Media Query&lt;/a&gt; by Eric Bailey.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;video&#34;&gt;Video&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QhnIZh0xwk0&#34;&gt;Infinite Canvas 6: Vestibular Disorders and Accessible Animation&lt;/a&gt; Rachel Nabors interviews Greg Tarnoff.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;more&#34;&gt;More‚Ä¶&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To stay updated on the topic, I‚Äôd really recommend you follow Val Head and Rachel Nabors. One of these days I‚Äôll add comments to my blog so folks can add their own suggestions, but &lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/laurakalbag&#34;&gt;if you‚Äôve got any further recommendations, please tweet me!&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/bookmarked-animation/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòBookmarked: Animation‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In February, there were two podcasts released featuring interviews with me! Both focused on ethical design and privacy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;codenewbie&#34;&gt;CodeNewbie&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.codenewbie.org/podcast/what-should-developers-know-about-online-privacy&#34;&gt;CodeNewbie Season 3 Episode 4: What should developers know about online privacy? with Laura Kalbag&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CodeNewbie is a fantastic podcast by Saron Yitbarek featuring interviews that introduce topics to people who are new to coding. You can &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.codenewbie.org/podcast/what-should-developers-know-about-online-privacy&#34;&gt;find the podcast on the CodeNewbie site&lt;/a&gt; along with a full transcript. One note is that I am continually muddling up the &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Data_Protection_Regulation&#34;&gt;GDPR&lt;/a&gt; acronym, calling the GDPR the ‚ÄúGeneral Directive Privacy Regulation‚Äù when it is actually ‚ÄúGeneral Data Protection Regulation.‚Äù Ugh, acronyms‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;digital-mindfulness&#34;&gt;Digital Mindfulness&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://digitalmindfulness.net/96-ethical-data-design-laura-kalbag/&#34;&gt;Digital Mindfulness #96 Ethical Data &amp;amp; Design with Laura Kalbag&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Digital Mindfulness is a podcast by Lawrence Ampofo looking at ‚Äúdigital experiences that focus on time well spent.‚Äù As I mentioned to Lawrence, I do not agree with a lot of the work in this area (see addendum below), so it made for an interesting interview which disagrees with many of the podcast‚Äôs previous guests. You can &lt;a href=&#34;https://digitalmindfulness.net/96-ethical-data-design-laura-kalbag/&#34;&gt;find the podcast on the Digital Mindfulness site&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;addendum&#34;&gt;Addendum&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Six hours later‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Yesterday &lt;a href=&#34;https://ar.al&#34;&gt;Aral&lt;/a&gt; sent me a link to an article: [‚ÄòBe Wary of Silicon Valley‚Äôs Guilty Conscience: on The Center for Humane Technology‚Äô] (&lt;a href=&#34;https://librarianshipwreck.wordpress.com/2018/02/13/be-wary-of-silicon-valleys-guilty-conscience-on-the-center-for-humane-technology/)&#34;&gt;https://librarianshipwreck.wordpress.com/2018/02/13/be-wary-of-silicon-valleys-guilty-conscience-on-the-center-for-humane-technology/)&lt;/a&gt;. Upon reading it today, I realised this perfectly summarises why I take issue with the previous guests on the Digital Mindfulness podcast. (And in a far more eloquent and coherent manner than I could ever muster.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúThe [Center For Humane Technology] senses that there is anger in the air towards the big tech companies, and it pulls a clever bait and switch by acknowledging that there is a problem but then insisting that the people who caused the problem can be trusted to fix it.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I recommend you [read the full article on the LibrarianShipwreck site] (&lt;a href=&#34;https://librarianshipwreck.wordpress.com/2018/02/13/be-wary-of-silicon-valleys-guilty-conscience-on-the-center-for-humane-technology/)&#34;&gt;https://librarianshipwreck.wordpress.com/2018/02/13/be-wary-of-silicon-valleys-guilty-conscience-on-the-center-for-humane-technology/)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/podcasts-february-2018/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòPodcasts, February 2018‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Probably the coolest I‚Äôve ever sounded‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Last week Ind.ie was featured in a Guardian article, &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/feb/01/punk-rock-internet-diy-rebels-working-replace-tech-giants-snoopers-charter&#34;&gt;‚ÄòThe punk rock internet ‚Äì how DIY ‚Äã‚Äãrebels ‚Äãare working to ‚Äãreplace the tech giants.‚Äô&lt;/a&gt; We were interviewed by John Harris, and I think he did a really great job of explaining what we do and why we do it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not having massive experience in being interviewed, I was a little nervous that I‚Äôd sound a bit daft, especially as I‚Äôm nowhere near as eloquent as Aral. But overall, I think the quotes were good and it works as a primer that I‚Äôll be sharing whenever somebody asks what we do at Ind.ie!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There‚Äôs a nice little paragraph where I sum up the why of it all‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúI got into the web because I liked the democracy of it,‚Äù says Kalbag, who has just published a book titled Accessibility for Everyone, about innovating in a way that includes those who technology too often ignores ‚Äì not least people with disabilities. ‚ÄúI want to be able to be in a society where I have control over my information, and other people do as well. Being a woman in technology, you can see how hideously unequal things are and how people building these systems don‚Äôt care about anyone other than themselves. I think we have to have technology that serves everybody ‚Äì not just rich, straight, white guys.‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;



