    /&gt;
      &lt;/a&gt;


&lt;p&gt;As I mention in the article, I see a lot of redundant and unsemantic HTML while I‚Äôm working on &lt;a href=&#34;https://better.fyi&#34;&gt;Better&lt;/a&gt;. HTML is often seen as easy, and therefore not worth learning in detail. It‚Äôs frustrating because HTML is one of the few completely unavoidable technologies of the web. It doesn‚Äôt take much to better understand how to use it effectively, and it can make a huge difference to the accessibility of a web page.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/semantic-html-on-24-ways/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòSemantic HTML on 24 Ways‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please excuse the wonkiness of my site. I am iterating on a new design, including all new backend. It‚Äôs static!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Because I apparently like to be stressed, I had a hard time limit for deploying this new design (today!) This means some of the content is a little garbled, and a lot of the CSS, particularly the colour schemes, needs refining in places.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For now I won‚Äôt be publicising this new design, so if you‚Äôre here and you‚Äôre seeing this, &lt;em&gt;shhh!&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/wonky-for-now/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòWonky for now‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After three years of work, I can finally tell you that I‚Äôve written a book for &lt;a href=&#34;https://abookapart.com&#34;&gt;A Book Apart&lt;/a&gt; about web accessibility called &lt;a href=&#34;https://abookapart.com/products/accessibility-for-everyone&#34;&gt;Accessibility For Everyone&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;portrait&#39;
      width=&#39;600&#39; height=&#39;927&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-for-everyone/aba-cover_hu04488ae39bdcc385b30be63869984d20_76108_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/accessibility-for-everyone/aba-cover_hu04488ae39bdcc385b30be63869984d20_76108_500x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 500w,/accessibility-for-everyone/aba-cover.png 600w&#39;
      src=&#39;aba-cover.png&#39; alt=&#39;Book cover for Accessibility For Everyone by Laura Kalbag. Book 23 from A Book Apart. Foreword by Heydon Pickering&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In case you‚Äôve not heard of web accessibility (you wouldn‚Äôt be the first!), web accessibility is the degree to which a website is usable by as many people as possible. A lot of material around accessibility focus on making websites usable by people with different types of disabilities and impairments, but designing inclusively for a wide range of needs will generally make websites more usable for &lt;em&gt;everyone&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is a huge wealth of information about accessibility from accessibility experts on the web. But where do you start? This is why I wrote Accessibility For Everyone. I want to help you learn the foundations of accessibility, and point you in the direction of the accessibility experts I learn from so we can keep making the web better.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Accessibility For Everyone will be published in a few months, and you can &lt;a href=&#34;https://abookapart.com/products/accessibility-for-everyone&#34;&gt;sign up to be notified when we launch on the A Book Apart website&lt;/a&gt;. If you forget, don‚Äôt worry, I‚Äôll probably be going on about this for a long time to come‚Ä¶ üòâ&lt;/p&gt;
