&lt;h3 id=&#34;how-do-they-know&#34;&gt;How do they know?&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But how else could Facebook have known?&lt;/p&gt;


    &lt;a
      href=&#39;http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2016/03/10/facebook-button-violates-privacy&#39;
    &gt;

    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1280&#39; height=&#39;720&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/074_hu6d9e4e7a57527e6fc3ceef2f5a8c7790_626991_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/074_hu6d9e4e7a57527e6fc3ceef2f5a8c7790_626991_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/074_hu6d9e4e7a57527e6fc3ceef2f5a8c7790_626991_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/074_hu6d9e4e7a57527e6fc3ceef2f5a8c7790_626991_1200x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 1200w,/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/074.jpg 1280w&#39;
      src=&#39;074.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Screenshot of CBS news article on Facebook buttons violating privacy&#39;
    /&gt;
      &lt;/a&gt;


&lt;p&gt;If I was browsing funeral-related sites, maybe Facebook would have that information if those sites had Facebook Share Buttons or Facebook login. As &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2016/03/10/facebook-button-violates-privacy&#34;&gt;this article in SBS News&lt;/a&gt; points out, those Facebook buttons track you across the web, violating your privacy. (Also note the hypocrisy of this news site using multiple Facebook buttons on this article.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You can find out some of the things Facebook knows about you in your Ad Preferences.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1280&#39; height=&#39;720&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/079_hu06553a3b18da4aae16cbfa94f65ebdaf_284372_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/079_hu06553a3b18da4aae16cbfa94f65ebdaf_284372_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/079_hu06553a3b18da4aae16cbfa94f65ebdaf_284372_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/079_hu06553a3b18da4aae16cbfa94f65ebdaf_284372_1200x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 1200w,/digital-assistants-facebook-quizzes-and-fake-news-you-wont-believe-what-happens-next/079.jpg 1280w&#39;
      src=&#39;079.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;More of my Facebook ad preferences including Away from Family, Expat (UK), iPhone 7, Frequent International Travellers, All iOS Devices&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But as ProPublica point out, Facebook doesn‚Äôt tell its users everything it really knows about them:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúWhat the [Facebook ads] page doesn‚Äôt say is that those sources include detailed dossiers obtained from commercial data brokers about users‚Äô online lives. Nor does Facebook show users any of the often remarkably detailed information it gets from those brokers.‚Äù‚Äî&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.propublica.org/article/facebook-doesnt-tell-users-everything-it-really-knows-about-them&#34;&gt;Julia Angwin, Terry Parris Jr.and Surya Mattu, December 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôll come back to data brokers later.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúThe fundamental purpose of most people at Facebook working on data is to influence and alter people‚Äôs moods and behaviour.They are doing it all the time to make you like stories more, to click on more ads, to spend more time on the site.‚Äù &lt;a href=&#34;http://andrewledvina.com/code/2014/07/04/10-ways-facebook-is-the-devil.html&#34;&gt;A data scientist who previously worked at Facebook&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If your first thought is ‚Äúbut isn‚Äôt that what we‚Äôre all trying to do‚Äù, you need to watch some sci-fi. The Nosedive episode from Black Mirror series 3 may seem far-fetched, but we are already participating in this ranking. It‚Äôs just not visible to us.&lt;/p&gt;



