&lt;p&gt;As time goes by, the tearful moments have become less, but I‚Äôm often shaken. Throughout 2015 and 2016, I‚Äôve had days of sudden drops in mood, going back to feeling distracted and odd. I didn‚Äôt realise until fairly recently that those drops weren‚Äôt¬†always¬†random turns. Sadly, 2016 has been noticeably full of high-profile deaths. Somebody I can‚Äôt remember wrote a kind tweet advising all to take care of their friends during those times; the massive coverage and shared emotional distress can affect those who have experienced loss themselves. I‚Äôve always tried to be empathetic to &lt;a href=&#34;http://everydayfeminism.com/2015/06/guide-to-triggering/&#34;&gt;triggering&lt;/a&gt;, but I‚Äôd never experienced anything like it myself. I was being triggered by the news; other people‚Äôs sad experiences were making me feel those feelings all over again. It can seem¬†a bit selfish to have to take care of myself when others are suffering more recent pain, but it‚Äôs hard to tell my biology to behave selflessly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As the weepy incidents lessen, remembering my mum and granny becomes less about suddenly remembering they‚Äôre not there, and more remembering the fun and silly stuff. With two strong personalities like them, the missing holes are very big, but the memories are all the more enjoyable. The family knows exactly what both of them would say about any given situation and can parrot it to each other convincingly. We‚Äôll always miss them, just hopefully less painfully.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm never really sure what to say when people ask about my bereavements, how I‚Äôm feeling, or even how I‚Äôve been¬†recently. Knowing is hard and dwelling on the matter isn‚Äôt much fun either. Everybody will inevitably experience the loss of someone very close to them in the course of their lifetime. It‚Äôs probably a more horrible realisation than realising we ourselves are going to die. But like many other mental health-related issues, it‚Äôs normal. Because of that I‚Äôm sorry I don‚Äôt have any useful advice or uplifting wisdom as part of &lt;a href=&#34;http://geekmentalhelp.com/&#34;&gt;#geekmentalhelp week&lt;/a&gt;. I‚Äôm not a professional. And sometimes all the rest of us can do is share what hurts.&lt;/p&gt;
