    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&#34;practical-typography&#34;&gt;Practical typography&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs slightly less obvious when it comes to the practical part of web typography. In order to choose typefaces that work for our projects, we need to really understand what we want from a typeface, and what we aim to achieve through typography.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We need to remember that typography exists to represent content, and so it‚Äôs always worthwhile to read the text before we design it. Our aim is to invite the reader in, and make the text appear easy to read, not an intimidating mass. Typography should also reveal the meaning of the text. Comic Sans isn‚Äôt appropriate for a formal restaurant site, and a swirling script typeface isn‚Äôt appropriate for the website of a party clown.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.070_hu1b232b8f3d8060495db23c57b2c3cd57_346229_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.070_hu1b232b8f3d8060495db23c57b2c3cd57_346229_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.070_hu1b232b8f3d8060495db23c57b2c3cd57_346229_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.070.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.070.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;A paragraph set in Blackoak Std, and a paragraph set in Heinemann&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Blackoak Std makes for chunky intimidating body text, Heinemann makes for a more inviting paragraph.&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When we read through the text, we can understand where it needs special treatment: where does the structure and order need to be made clear? The connections and differences between elements should be shown. The visual relationships between the text and other elements should reflect their real relationship. A heading is more important than a paragraph, and its importance should be revealed through size differences at the very least. All of these factors can be combined together to induce an ideal state for reading.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.073_hu2b11fb647e71088ea5e4a9e199964f1e_278767_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.073_hu2b11fb647e71088ea5e4a9e199964f1e_278767_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.073_hu2b11fb647e71088ea5e4a9e199964f1e_278767_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.073.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.073.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;A paragraph with larger and smaller headings&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Clear headings, links, and typographic hierarchy.&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The easiest win in accessible typography is just getting the text at a readable size.¬†The most readable typeface is unreadable at a small size,¬†yet so many sizes squeeze tiny text so they can fit more into a layout.¬†Responsive design should have made it more obvious that scrolling is perfectly acceptable.¬†The smaller the x-height (the height of a lowercase x),¬†the bigger your text will need to be in order to be readable.



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.071_hu5f1dbf75444570288612d4777ee9ce2e_265303_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.071_hu5f1dbf75444570288612d4777ee9ce2e_265303_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.071_hu5f1dbf75444570288612d4777ee9ce2e_265303_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.071.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.071.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Different sized paragraphs at 10px, 12px, 18px and 24px&#39;
    /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;readability&#34;&gt;Readability&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Whilst good structure and a strong differentiation between elements will help a reader understand how to read the text, the key to accessible typography is in choosing a readable font.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Uniform texture is more important than the shapes of the individual characters in a typeface. Typography isn‚Äôt the same as logo design. When we look at the relationship between the letters, an even texture helps our eyes flow over the text, not getting caught up on unexpected spaces and distracting shapes.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.077_hue5bc9a08b1ebb172f53e4eda1a247206_300479_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.077_hue5bc9a08b1ebb172f53e4eda1a247206_300479_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.077_hue5bc9a08b1ebb172f53e4eda1a247206_300479_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.077.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.077.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Paragraphs of uniform and uneven texture&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;If you squint at the top paragraph, it has an even texture. If you squint at the lower paragraph, it‚Äôs a much more blobby, uneven texture.&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Since high resolution displays became the designers‚Äô favourite, thin text is all the rage. Apple did it, and now everybody else does too. But so often thin text is just too thin, making the text appear very light against the background, making it harder to read. Heavy text also doesn‚Äôt provide enough contrast between the text and the background, as its chunkiness makes it hard to distinguish letterforms. You want to choose the Goldilocks of typeface weights: not too heavy, not too light. A high contrast of crisp letterforms with enough space around and between the shapes will make text much easier to read.



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.078_hu4e66b28950010fcb7a6a8d56a41c5bca_295327_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.078_hu4e66b28950010fcb7a6a8d56a41c5bca_295327_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.078_hu4e66b28950010fcb7a6a8d56a41c5bca_295327_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.078.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.078.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Light and heavy paragraphs of text&#39;
    /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The lines of each letterform also need attention. Serif fonts, in particular, often contrast thick and thin lines within one letter. Your eyes are naturally drawn to the thick lines, and less to the thin, which creates an uneven and distracting texture, making it harder to read.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.079_huea309153396b600a03b9dbb44a610bc5_179031_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.079_huea309153396b600a03b9dbb44a610bc5_179031_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.079_huea309153396b600a03b9dbb44a610bc5_179031_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.079.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.079.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;High-contrast serif&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;High-contrast serif&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We also want to avoid complex details in the letterforms. The loops in Giddyup Std are cute, but overcrowd body text too much. You can see how our reading would be disrupted and tripped up by a loop or a curl in an unusual place.



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.080_huf6bac5b191624eb1f9640cdbc493bd09_210507_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.080_huf6bac5b191624eb1f9640cdbc493bd09_210507_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.080_huf6bac5b191624eb1f9640cdbc493bd09_210507_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.080.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.080.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;A paragraph set in the curly loopy GiddyUp Std&#39;
    /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Another feature of letterforms that affects the readability of a typeface is the counters. These are the spaces inside the letters. Sometimes they‚Äôre open, like Cs, and sometimes they‚Äôre closed, like Os. We need a clear distinction between the open and closed counters, so you can easily tell them apart. Otherwise a phrase like Rococo Cocoon could easily be misread as Rooooo Ooooon.



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.081_hu4b024c6f8f00fb8060c90f3d7e5226a2_180440_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.081_hu4b024c6f8f00fb8060c90f3d7e5226a2_180440_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.081_hu4b024c6f8f00fb8060c90f3d7e5226a2_180440_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.081.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.081.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Embrionic has very closed counters, Museo Sans has more open counters&#39;
    /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Some typefaces are specifically designed to be easier for people with cognitive difficulties. Heinemann is a beautiful typeface designed in-house at Heinemann educational publishing for young readers. The ascenders and descenders (the parts of the letters that ascend above the lowercase letters, and the parts that descend below the lowercase letters) are emphasised to make it easier for readers to distinguish between letters. The letterforms such as lowercase a and g are drawn in the same shape as we learn to write by hand, to make them more recognisable.&lt;/p&gt;


    &lt;a
      href=&#39;http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/fw-heinemann/heinemann/gallery.html&#39;
    &gt;

    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.083_hua072f77edebc58417f87531adf35ea4e_260594_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.083_hua072f77edebc58417f87531adf35ea4e_260594_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.083_hua072f77edebc58417f87531adf35ea4e_260594_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.083.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.083.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Heinemann type family&#39;
    /&gt;
      &lt;/a&gt;


&lt;p&gt;While many designers look down on Comic Sans, it shares those same early-learner letterforms as Heinemann, and is often favoured by teachers in classrooms as the letterforms are the same as those the children are using when they‚Äôre learning to write.&lt;/p&gt;


    &lt;a
      href=&#39;http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/ascender/comic-sans/&#39;
    &gt;

    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.084_hu1756331591a968e3753f9fe787ac04ca_278949_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.084_hu1756331591a968e3753f9fe787ac04ca_278949_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.084_hu1756331591a968e3753f9fe787ac04ca_278949_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.084.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.084.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Comic Sans typeface&#39;
    /&gt;
      &lt;/a&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Read Regular, Dyslexie and Open Dyslexic are both fonts designed with dyslexic readers in mind, but with very different approaches. Read Regular is more similar to Heinemann in that it takes a sans serif style, and simple letterforms to assist in readability. However Dyslexie and Open Dyslexic take a very different approach, with noticeably heavier sections around the baseline to prevent readers from accidentally reading the letters upside down (a common issue in dyslexia.) The counters have been opened up, and similar looking letters (such as n and m, or vwy), have been adjusted in shape and height so they look different, and are easier to tell apart.&lt;/p&gt;


    &lt;a
      href=&#39;http://www.readregular.com/english/typography.html&#39;
    &gt;

    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.085_hua37896bb5b0d8f8c04d5636dfe35ab5b_947232_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.085_hua37896bb5b0d8f8c04d5636dfe35ab5b_947232_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.085_hua37896bb5b0d8f8c04d5636dfe35ab5b_947232_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.085.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.085.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Read Regular typeface&#39;
    /&gt;
      &lt;/a&gt;




    &lt;a
      href=&#39;http://opendyslexic.org&#39;
    &gt;

    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.086_huda20d2ecf24affd9fcac632b62c5e1d9_523431_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.086_huda20d2ecf24affd9fcac632b62c5e1d9_523431_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.086_huda20d2ecf24affd9fcac632b62c5e1d9_523431_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.086.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.086.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Dyslexie and Open Dyslexic typefaces&#39;
    /&gt;
      &lt;/a&gt;


&lt;h3 id=&#34;colour&#34;&gt;Colour&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&#34;how-we-interact-with-colour&#34;&gt;How we interact with colour&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When we‚Äôre designing for the web, we tend interact with colour via colour¬†pickers.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.088_hu4befc4c93301c25efe3142db626a001d_154026_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.088_hu4befc4c93301c25efe3142db626a001d_154026_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.088_hu4befc4c93301c25efe3142db626a001d_154026_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.088.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.088.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Colour pickers&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Colour wheel (left) is a more classic layout, with blended hues in a ring. The colour spectrum on the right is more recognisable as it takes the blends you see in the colour wheel, and adds white and black to give you varying shades. The bars in the middle are usually sliders, and allow you to slide between different hues, saturation and brightness for your chosen colour.&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The benefit of using hues visualised on a colour wheel is that you‚Äôre more likely to find colours that work well in a palette. You can pick from side-by-side colours for an analogous blend, or from colours opposite each other on the wheel for a more striking colour contrast.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.096_hua6d8331b94ee7a73cd147fe1308973d6_101126_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.096_hua6d8331b94ee7a73cd147fe1308973d6_101126_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.096_hua6d8331b94ee7a73cd147fe1308973d6_101126_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.096.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.096.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Colour picking with droppers on opposite sides of the colour wheel&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Colour picking from opposite sides of the colour wheel&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But the accessibility of colour is more than just picking two different colours. In order to make our foreground text readable against our background colour, we need &lt;strong&gt;contrast&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When we‚Äôre trying to find a good contrast, the colour wheel isn‚Äôt much help. The key is the sliders for brightness and saturation. A high contrast is caused by a greater difference the foreground and background brightness, and the foreground and background saturation.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.105_hu0196dc34611744b2b1798a52d735b678_165256_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.105_hu0196dc34611744b2b1798a52d735b678_165256_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.105_hu0196dc34611744b2b1798a52d735b678_165256_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.105.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.105.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Varying the brightness for colour contrast&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Varying the brightness for colour contrast&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For example, a blue background with blue text of a similar lightness will be hard to read, whereas a lighter blue against a darker blue is much easier, making a more accessible foreground-background contrast.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.106_hu7b5ea345ff1137f10244e485a1fa6b13_156996_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.106_hu7b5ea345ff1137f10244e485a1fa6b13_156996_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.106_hu7b5ea345ff1137f10244e485a1fa6b13_156996_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.106.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.106.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Different strengths of saturation, with greater difference comes higher contrast&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Varying the saturation for colour contrast&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The same applies to saturation. Deeply saturated yellow text will have a low contrast against a similarly deeply saturated yellow. However, using a desaturated yellow in the background makes for a more accessible foreground-background contrast.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.107_huefb416f6ab86dda6de528ec1f3ca8c3e_181149_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.107_huefb416f6ab86dda6de528ec1f3ca8c3e_181149_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.107_huefb416f6ab86dda6de528ec1f3ca8c3e_181149_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.107.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.107.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;High contrast with different colours, but the same contrast between brightness and saturation as before&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Using the different colour pairs with the same brightness and saturation as before&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The same rules apply even when you‚Äôre using different colours for the foreground and background.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Very high contrast foreground and background combinations can also suffer from accessibility problems. Issues with high contrast aren‚Äôt talked about as often, but can hurt your eyes, and be particularly problematic for people with dyslexia.



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.108_hu9919f7b3f46635b6673d32d5992520f9_112381_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.108_hu9919f7b3f46635b6673d32d5992520f9_112381_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.108_hu9919f7b3f46635b6673d32d5992520f9_112381_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.108.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.108.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Extreme high contrast between bright green background and black text, and white text on a black background&#39;
    /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To avoid screaming high contrast, I would recommend softening the difference between the foreground and background values slightly, bringing one value slightly closer to the other. By tweaking these contrasts slightly, they‚Äôre much easier on the eyes.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.109_hu46a2ab3526a05633d9b5e3864099fae8_130470_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.109_hu46a2ab3526a05633d9b5e3864099fae8_130470_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.109_hu46a2ab3526a05633d9b5e3864099fae8_130470_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.109.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.109.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;A slightly less saturated green and a slightly brighter grey&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Softening the high contrast values&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;accessibility-and-branding&#34;&gt;Accessibility and Branding&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If we considered accessibility at a brand level, what would that be like?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What if we designed our logos and associated colour palettes with an accessible colour contrast in mind? I‚Äôve been doing this for years, not really thinking much of it. As a designer who usually created a logo and would then go on to design and develop a site around it, it just made sense to me.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.111_huef17ffdbe6ba387b5ee35c3c924d819a_235215_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.111_huef17ffdbe6ba387b5ee35c3c924d819a_235215_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.111_huef17ffdbe6ba387b5ee35c3c924d819a_235215_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.111.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.111.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Logo designs with accessible text colours&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Some of my old logo designs&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If we make the colours accessible, then the colours we use on the site can be consistently on-brand later on; we won‚Äôt suddenly need to use a darker colour for our body text because our brand‚Äôs colour palette produces unreadable results.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.113_hu74876f8f95456e8b833fdcffc300517c_323699_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.113_hu74876f8f95456e8b833fdcffc300517c_323699_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.113_hu74876f8f95456e8b833fdcffc300517c_323699_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.113.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.113.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Early typography-based logo designs&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Some early designs for logos, with accessible, web-compatible typography&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What if we choose our logo and brand typefaces with readability and web typography in mind, not just which typeface has three letters that look good for our logo? Maybe if our logo is a swirling script face, we should consider a complementary body text early on, when we‚Äôre designing the rest of our brand. This could prevent us getting caught out when our site designer or developer has to pick a completely off-brand typeface because our brand typography is so hard to read as body text.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.114_hu3b6e846fa720d42d5c0e1c8afee34585_535799_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.114_hu3b6e846fa720d42d5c0e1c8afee34585_535799_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.114_hu3b6e846fa720d42d5c0e1c8afee34585_535799_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/accessibility-by-design/Accessibility-By-Design.114.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;Accessibility-By-Design.114.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;A script based logo with an upright sans serif body text. They don‚Äôt quite work together.&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;A beautiful script logo and beautiful web typography, but the brand doesn‚Äôt quite match up.&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The earlier we, as designers, learn to consider accessibility, the less likely we‚Äôll have our designs diluted and confused further down the line.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;strategies-for-involving-accessibility-from-the-beginning-of-the-design-process&#34;&gt;Strategies for involving accessibility from the beginning of the design process&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So I have a few simple strategies for involving accessibility from the beginning of the design process‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;understanding-accessibility&#34;&gt;Understanding accessibility&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Just understanding why it‚Äôs worth making our sites accessible is a big first step. Only the most foolish people would learn a little about accessibility and not hold it in their heads for every future project. I don‚Äôt mean having to become an expert overnight, but just knowing little tips and tricks to make sites better.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;constraints-1&#34;&gt;Constraints&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Considering accessibility as a constraint is a complementary to the other strategies. It‚Äôs a more specific way of thinking, as you‚Äôre always referring back to accessibility.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;sitting-in-on-testing-and-focus-groups&#34;&gt;Sitting in on testing and focus groups&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When we hear and witness the experiences of others, it‚Äôs much easier to:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;a) understand how other people don‚Äôt interact with the web in the same way we do&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;b) understand the multitude of ways people CAN interact with the web and how we might better serve their needs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;being-involved-in-human-research&#34;&gt;Being involved in human research&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Being involved in human research is very similar to the previous point, but is more about being ahead of the work, rather than behind it. We need to be researching and understanding human interaction before we start a single task.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If we‚Äôre only discovering issues with accessibility in a later testing phase, we‚Äôre already behind the curve.&lt;/p&gt;
In the talk I gave this morning, I then went on to talk about the 3 Rs of Ethical Design. But rather than explain it to you here, I think you should &lt;a href=&#34;https://ind.ie/you-are-the-product/&#34;&gt;watch Aral cover it in his talk Beyond The Camera Panopticon: You Are The Product&lt;/a&gt; (the part on Ethical Design starts at around the 53 minute mark.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;make-accessibility-more-accessible&#34;&gt;Make accessibility more accessible&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If we want to make accessibility more accessible to different roles in our organisations,¬†we need to learn how to better incorporate it into our existing processes.¬†Acknowledging accessibility as a constraint from the outset ensures we have it as a point of reference at every step in the process.¬†This also deliberately avoids looking at accessibility as some kind of checklist.¬†Designers need to understand that accessibility can no more be ticked off a list than user experience can. These aren‚Äôt checklist tasks, but are¬†our goals, our focuses, and our approaches.



