&lt;p&gt;This post is so good, and so incredibly valuable, that it‚Äôs deserving of more than just a passing tweet. Julie Pagano has written about ‚Äò&lt;a href=&#34;http://juliepagano.com/blog/2014/08/26/building-a-diverse-speaker-lineup/&#34;&gt;Building a Diverse Speaker Lineup&lt;/a&gt;.‚Äô This should be the go-to post for conference organisers, and it should be read as soon as you‚Äôre even thinking about organising an event.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Julie‚Äôs post doesn‚Äôt just explain &lt;em&gt;why&lt;/em&gt; you want a diverse lineup (also worth reading on this topic: &lt;a href=&#34;https://aralbalkan.com/notes/on-design-and-diversity/&#34;&gt;Aral‚Äôs post, On design and diversity&lt;/a&gt;), but also &lt;em&gt;how&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is not about collecting random people from a demographic to fill some token slot, so the mean people on the internet don‚Äôt yell at you.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm a woman, I‚Äôm not 100% white, and I‚Äôve spoken at (according to &lt;a href=&#34;http://lanyrd.com/profile/laurakalbag/&#34;&gt;Lanyrd&lt;/a&gt;) 30 events. Being invited to speak is still a very tricky situation. I‚Äôve had situations where I could very easily tell that I was invited at the last minute to be a token speaker to boost the diversity of the event. But I‚Äôve had far more situations where the organisers knew me, knew the kinds of things I like to talk about, and considered me a good fit. My experiences are largely very positive.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, as a ‚Äúminority‚Äù speaker you can feel a horrible amount of pressure to speak. There‚Äôs the feeling that if you say no, you‚Äôre allowing your groups to be under-represented. Or worse, the conference organiser can say ‚Äúwell I asked her, and she said no, so it‚Äôs &lt;strong&gt;her&lt;/strong&gt; fault we don‚Äôt have a diverse lineup.‚Äù It‚Äôs horrible and wrong, but it happens. And following the guidance in Julie‚Äôs post can help organisers understand how to approach speakers, and how to make their Call For Proposals more friendly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The other problem I have as a speaker is finding the event itself generally unfriendly and alienating. I am one of those people who feels intensely uncomfortable in a dark room with lots of alcohol and loud music. I‚Äôve avoided a lot of after parties because of casual sexist remarks that made me feel like I didn‚Äôt belong there. Julie‚Äôs section on Conference Environment can help prevent these awkward situations, and make everyone feel more welcome.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In response to a few organisers complaining about being bullied for their event‚Äôs lack of diversity, Julie finishes on a brilliant note:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Organizing a conference is hard work. Nobody is denying that. Working on making your conference diverse should be part of that work. I just gave you some insight into how you can do that. If you don‚Äôt want to do the hard work, you may receive criticism or people may not want to attend your event. That‚Äôs not bullying. That is holding you accountable for failing to do your job well. Work hard and avoid falling into the trap of the homogeneous conference lineup.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;


