&lt;p&gt;Yesterday I gave a talk at &lt;a href=&#34;http://kiwiparty.fr/&#34;&gt;KiwiParty&lt;/a&gt; in Strasbourg. KiwiParty is a lovely conference, but all of the speakers spoke in French, to the French audience. Except me. I speak a little bit of (A-Level) French, but I certainly couldn‚Äôt give a talk in French.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;designing-for-accessibility&#34;&gt;Designing for accessibility&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My talk was about Designing for accessibility. I wouldn‚Äôt be setting a very good example if I was to give a talk about accessibility which was hard to understand for 99% of the audience. I talked to my friend, &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.inpixelitrust.fr/&#34;&gt;St√©phanie Walter&lt;/a&gt;, one of the organisers of KiwiParty, about getting my slides translated into French. St√©phanie very generously offered to translate my slides, on top of all the other hard work she was doing with organising the conference and creating the lovely (and very accessible!) &lt;a href=&#34;http://kiwiparty.fr/&#34; title=&#34;KiwiParty website&#34;&gt;website&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;



