	&lt;div class=&#34;comment-entry&#34;&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;Thanks for sharing all this pages.
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs quite good to see that your sketches are ‚Äì; in my opinion ‚Äì; far away from a perfect ‚Äúdrawing‚Äù and that a logo isn‚Äôt born as you can see it in its final state but it ‚Äúgrew up‚Äù with some iterations on it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While being not really good at all this painting stuff it encourages me keep on noting down my ideas with pictures and some rough lines.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Again, thanks for sharing this, Laura! :)&lt;/p&gt;	&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/a-look-inside-a-designers-sketchbook/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòA look inside a designer‚Äôs sketchbook‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was slow to post about&lt;a href=&#34;https://the-pastry-box-project.net/laura-kalbag/2014-april-19&#34;&gt; my April Pastry Box post&lt;/a&gt; as &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/a-little-realign/&#34; title=&#34;A little realign&#34;&gt;my realign&lt;/a&gt; got in the way. It was really a little insecure thought about how my writing and thinking is improving, but I‚Äôm finding it hard.&lt;/p&gt;


    &lt;a
      href=&#39;https://the-pastry-box-project.net/laura-kalbag/2014-april-19&#39;
    &gt;

    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;720&#39; height=&#39;535&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/aprils-pastry-box-thought-on-writing/pastry-box-april_hu3ded594a5adb5474e6ad6c45474226f1_60409_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/aprils-pastry-box-thought-on-writing/pastry-box-april_hu3ded594a5adb5474e6ad6c45474226f1_60409_500x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 500w,/aprils-pastry-box-thought-on-writing/pastry-box-april.png 720w&#39;
      src=&#39;pastry-box-april.png&#39; alt=&#39;Laura Kalbag on The Pastry Box, Saturday 19th April 2014&#39;
    /&gt;
      &lt;/a&gt;


&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/aprils-pastry-box-thought-on-writing/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòApril‚Äôs Pastry Box thought on writing‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Things are looking a bit different around here. It‚Äôs not a redesign so much as a &lt;a href=&#34;http://alistapart.com/article/redesignrealign&#34;&gt;realign&lt;/a&gt;. I‚Äôve been tinkering for a few months, and finally got to the point where I‚Äôm happy to push it live (even though there‚Äôs more I could do.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There were a few particular goals for this redesign:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;rewrite-the-css&#34;&gt;Rewrite the CSS&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I lived in fear that someone might look closely at my CSS. My last redesign came about when responsive web design was still young, and I was incredibly foolish. I linked to three different stylesheets in my header, one for 320px and up, one for 768px and up, and one for 1024px and up. There were some ‚Äúminor‚Äù breakpoints in these stylesheets, but yes, I was using fairly device-based breakpoints, and that was three HTTP requests in the head. Certainly not ideal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The previous version was also a peculiar Sass/plain CSS hybrid as I‚Äôd started learning Sass a few months into the redesign. As Sass is so easy to integrate into ordinary CSS, it wasn‚Äôt too problematic, but I knew I could lessen repetition and make the structure of my CSS much easier to maintain if I moved it all into a consistent format.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now I‚Äôve rewritten all the CSS from scratch using Sass, and added in a few new techniques, such as flexbox, for some of the form elements. If you‚Äôre interested in how badly I write Sass, I‚Äôve uploaded those files (in the spirit of Dan Eden‚Äôs max CSS) into a /sass folder and you can find the file references in the main file, &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/wp-content/themes/laurakalbag-2014/sass/style.scss&#34;&gt;style.scss&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;reboot-the-typography&#34;&gt;Reboot the typography&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I love Avenir, I really do, but I was increasingly aware that it can be hard work to read as body text. After falling in love with &lt;a href=&#34;http://hvdfonts.com/#189-Brandon%20Text&#34; title=&#34;Brandon Text typeface&#34;&gt;Brandon Text&lt;/a&gt;, I decided it was a nice evolution from Avenir, keeping the geometric shapes but in a softer, more legible, way.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;721&#39; height=&#39;308&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/a-little-realign/previous-typography_huafbbd2b0d1ad9b27769e858e6e150aaa_62736_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/a-little-realign/previous-typography_huafbbd2b0d1ad9b27769e858e6e150aaa_62736_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/a-little-realign/previous-typography.jpg 721w&#39;
      src=&#39;previous-typography.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Avenir as display and body text&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Avenir as display and body text on the old version of my site&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I recently read Tim Brown‚Äôs fantastic &lt;a href=&#34;http://nicewebtype.com/notes/2013/04/23/pocket-guide-to-combining-typefaces/&#34;&gt;Combining Typefaces&lt;/a&gt;¬†book and felt encouraged to be braver with my typefaces choices. I didn‚Äôt want to just keep using different weights of the same family as I had before. After some &lt;a href=&#34;https://dribbble.com/shots/1510342-Freight-Micro-and-Brandon-Text-dilemma?list=users&amp;amp;offset=6&#34; title=&#34;Dribbble shots showing the process of my heading typeface choice&#34;&gt;deliberation&lt;/a&gt; and advice, I settled on &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.rosettatype.com/Arek&#34;&gt;Arek&lt;/a&gt; for headings, to add a bit of quirky personality to my site. This is the first time I‚Äôve used &lt;a href=&#34;http://fontdeck.com&#34;&gt;Fontdeck&lt;/a&gt; properly, and I‚Äôm really pleased with the quality of the font and the speedy rendering.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;721&#39; height=&#39;308&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/a-little-realign/new-typography_hue8c7f2d788a235a34c340601c54c271c_58326_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/a-little-realign/new-typography_hue8c7f2d788a235a34c340601c54c271c_58326_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/a-little-realign/new-typography.jpg 721w&#39;
      src=&#39;new-typography.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Arek for the display text, and Brandon Text for the body text&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Arek for the display, and Brandon Text for the body on the new realign&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm both self-hosting and using external JavaScript to pull in fonts for my site. Brandon Text is self-hosted whereas Arek is hosted on Fontdeck. I can‚Äôt quite make up my mind whether I prefer to suffer slow loading times on my self-hosted fonts, or the risk of my site depending on another site for the fonts to load with a font delivery service.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;simplify&#34;&gt;Simplify&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The illustrations had to go. I‚Äôm always trying to tame my temptation to over-decorate, and while the illustrations in the previous version were a nice responsive bonus for large screens, a cleaner design is less distracting.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
