&lt;p&gt;Using a Fitbit over the last year and a half has taught me that making your habits more visible in public makes you more likely to work harder. When you‚Äôre giving up a bad habit, often there‚Äôs not much stopping us from slipping back into the bad habits. So I am writing here, on Tuesday 27th August 2013 that¬†&lt;i&gt;I am giving up Red Bull&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;It sounds ridiculous, but I have a problem&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Fortunately I‚Äôve not got to the point where my teeth have dropped out or I have heart palpitations, but Red Bull has been my ‚Äúone last thing‚Äù for the last couple of years. I used to have a terrible diet, and barely exercised, which I wrote about a little in¬†&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/six-months-of-the-fitbit-and-the-new-fitbit-aria/&#34;&gt;my Fitbit review post&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm past that now, I do a lot of exercise and eat healthily but not to the point of obsession. But I‚Äôve still been drinking a lot of Red Bull. Last week I fooled myself thinking that if I swapped Red Bull for organic energy drinks, then it‚Äôd be ok. Yesterday I realised that I was just attempting to justify the bad habit. Most people just laugh when I tell them I drink a lot of Red Bull, but you know it‚Äôs bad when I tell you that I have Red Bull after breakfast.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Addictive personality&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Some people just seem to get addicted to things that much easier than others. I‚Äôm one of them. Luckily I‚Äôm addicted to exercise now, so it‚Äôs not always a bad thing. But through drinking so much Red Bull, I‚Äôm also addicted to caffeine and sugar. I‚Äôve tried giving up Red Bull before, but I just ended up eating more pick‚Äôn‚Äômix sweets. When I go on holiday or away, it‚Äôs often harder to find energy drinks, so I find myself drinking coffee (which I hate) or tea, loaded with sugar. I‚Äôm determined to not replace it with other bad sugary things. I‚Äôm writing this here so I really do it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Highs and lows&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Caffeine and sugar are great, but the rush is so impermanent. I always say I do my best design work when I‚Äôm hopped up on caffeine and sugar. I think that‚Äôs probably me making excuses for drinking so much Red Bull! I hope that getting caffeine out of my system will result in a more consistent working pace, where I don‚Äôt feel like I have to adhere to all these conditions I‚Äôve invented for myself in order to be productive.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Stand by for the whining&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I know I‚Äôm going to be annoying, and sleepy. Sympathy should probably be directed towards&lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/aral&#34;&gt;Aral&lt;/a&gt;, who has to put up with me. I don‚Äôt deserve any sympathy, I‚Äôm just doing what I should have done so long ago!&lt;/p&gt;
