&lt;p&gt;I know, this is a funny topic on which to base a blog post but I love the &lt;a href=&#34;http://unfinished.bz/&#34;&gt;Unfinished Business podcast&lt;/a&gt;, and I‚Äôd like to elaborate why in something more than a few &lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/laurakalbag/status/306038603950198785&#34;&gt;fawning tweets&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;business-but-not-suits&#34;&gt;Business, but not suits&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Business doesn‚Äôt feel like the right word to describe what I do. It‚Äôs a hobby that makes me enough money to support myself. The word ‚Äòbusiness‚Äô conjures up images of suits, handshakes and networking. Unfinished Business feels like a podcast about my kind of business. It‚Äôs not about synergising or maximising profits in the next quarter, it‚Äôs about how to do the best by our clients and ourselves.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;transparency-openness-honesty&#34;&gt;Transparency, openness, honesty&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The entire premise of the Unfinished Business podcast is to speak openly about business end of the web, design and creative industries. And Anna and Andy really do exactly that. They‚Äôre not saying things to impress people, they talk about mistakes they‚Äôve made and how they think they could do business better, and they‚Äôre not scared of talking about ‚Äútaboo‚Äù subjects, such as money. This means each episode is full of insights on how to get started working as a small business, and how to keep that small business running successfully.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It says it all over my site, honesty is really my thing. From me this might come in the form of over-sharing occasionally on Twitter, and often putting my foot in my mouth. Still, honesty feels like something that‚Äôs lacking in the business world. The web community that I know isn‚Äôt competitive, it‚Äôs sharing. Unfinished Business reflects this non-competitive sharing when Anna and Andy speak so honestly about business. They‚Äôre not doing a podcast to gain a competitive advantage against other developers and designers who don‚Äôt have podcasts, they‚Äôve just created a space to share experiences.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;ethics&#34;&gt;Ethics&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is what struck me today, and the reason why Unfinished Business resonates so much with me. Anna and Andy don‚Äôt talk about how to make money, they talk about how to do a good job for your clients. Today I listened to them discussing handing over files to clients when the business relationship has finished. Their priority was doing the right thing, and not making life difficult for that client after they‚Äôve moved on. This means so much. It‚Äôs one thing to be hardworking and good at your job, it‚Äôs quite another to be a good person.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These are good people. And &lt;a href=&#34;http://unfinished.bz/&#34;&gt;you should listen to their podcast&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;


