      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;220&#39; height=&#39;215&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/the-east-wing-podcast/east-wing.png 220w&#39;
      src=&#39;east-wing.png&#39; alt=&#39;The East Wing podcast&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/the-east-wing-podcast/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòThe East Wing podcast‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I used to not understand the fuss around women at conferences, I thought that we should all just carry on with what we were doing well already and not get caught up in needless controversy. I even &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/women-in/&#34; title=&#34;Women in‚Ä¶&#34;&gt;wrote a blog post saying exactly that a couple of years ago&lt;/a&gt;. I‚Äôd never experienced (to my knowledge) any difficulties because I was a woman.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;a-bit-uncomfortable&#34;&gt;A bit uncomfortable&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But then I started hearing more about/was exposed to women who did have bad experiences. And I attended a few events where I just didn‚Äôt feel comfortable. It took me a while to pinpoint why I didn‚Äôt feel right. I didn‚Äôt realise right away that it was the lack of diversity that made me feel singled out. I realised that it was also the reason I felt uncomfortable when I was invited to women-only events. It wasn‚Äôt because I want to be surrounded by women, it‚Äôs because I want to be surrounded by diversity. It‚Äôs unique perspectives that bring more interesting solutions to problems and promote innovation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;its-hard-to-know-if-youre-not-being-welcoming&#34;&gt;It‚Äôs hard to know if you‚Äôre not being welcoming&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At these events where I felt uncomfortable, I didn‚Äôt have any &lt;em&gt;bad&lt;/em&gt; experiences, it was more that I felt people didn‚Äôt expect me to be there; I wasn‚Äôt the target audience. So rarely in these situations is there gender-based discrimination, it‚Äôs usually just ignorant comments based on stereotypes like ‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt think you‚Äôd be a developer, I thought girls were usually designers.‚Äù It was always the case that the men making the comments or featuring scantily-clad women in their presentations didn‚Äôt realise the effect these things might have on the audience, or that they might be alienating people. This is half of the problem, when you‚Äôre someone who‚Äôs rarely on the receiving end of these things, it‚Äôs hard to understand the effect they could have on others.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;feeling-special&#34;&gt;Feeling special&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Something I think I was trying to protect in my defensive blog post was that sometimes I could see the upsides of being singled out. It made me feel special in my uniqueness, like I had something that no one else had, and I got more attention because of it. I‚Äôm a bit ashamed, but I‚Äôm not too angry at my former self because I think that‚Äôs a fairly normal thing to feel, everybody wants to feel like one in a million.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I was also a bit nervous, I didn‚Äôt want to have the spotlight put on me for the wrong reasons. I‚Äôd done a couple of talks at bar camps, and I quite liked the idea of doing more in the future. I didn‚Äôt want to be cast as ‚Äúthe token girl‚Äù speaker.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;why-its-worth-effecting-change&#34;&gt;Why it‚Äôs worth effecting change&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The big deal now is about the amount of women speakers at conferences, and it‚Äôs kind of an extension of the ‚Äúwomen attending conferences‚Äù, ‚Äúwomen in the industry‚Äù, ‚Äúwomen studying computing‚Äù problems. The thing is, this is a point where &lt;strong&gt;we can actually make a difference&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôd be very difficult for most of us to effect change in education, but it‚Äôs much easier for us to get more women representing the industry at conferences. This could hopefully then encourage more women to attend conferences, which would lead to more women in the industry, women studying computing subjects etc, and the same goes for other minority groups. I don‚Äôt think many people would argue that this is a bad thing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;quotas-at-conferences-theyre-not-the-only-possible-solution&#34;&gt;Quotas at conferences, they‚Äôre not the only possible solution‚Ä¶&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The next big controversy is about how we can manage this. Without resorting to quotas or all women speakers reluctant to accept speaking invitations without wondering ‚Äúam I only here because I‚Äôm a girl?‚Äù&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There‚Äôs currently a big problem with conference organisers who just aren‚Äôt that bothered about diversity in the industry. I can understand their hiding away from the issue, because actively trying to improve it is very very hard. There have been a &lt;a href=&#34;http://2012.jsconf.eu/2012/09/17/beating-the-odds-how-we-got-25-percent-women-speakers.html&#34;&gt;few posts&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://geekfeminism.org/2012/05/21/how-i-got-50-women-speakers-at-my-tech-conference/&#34;&gt;written about&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.startuplessonslearned.com/2012/11/solving-pipeline-problem.html&#34;&gt;how conferences have done this&lt;/a&gt;, but the main point is that organisers have been forced to look inside themselves and consider whether they pick their speakers objectively, without bias against minorities. Many organisers ask their friends to speak. It must be an awkward thing if you suddenly realise that, totally unintentionally, all your friends are white men.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;examining-ourselves&#34;&gt;Examining ourselves&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is a problem because most people couldn‚Äôt possibly identify this in themselves, and then those that do wouldn‚Äôt want to admit it anyway. It‚Äôs difficult to understand that we (society) tend to favour white men in authority roles (such as speaking at conferences) because that‚Äôs what our culture has taught us to want. You don‚Äôt have to be a white man to feel this way towards white men in authority either.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;fighting-our-biases&#34;&gt;Fighting our biases&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The way to combat these biases (whether they‚Äôre known or unknown, and whether we acknowledge them or not) is to ask conference organisers to review their speaker selection process. Especially if it seems to result in featuring one type of person. Nothing more than that. Quotas don‚Äôt help, because that just results in ‚Äútoken‚Äù speakers, but &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2013/01/a-simple-suggestion-to-help-phase-out-all-male-panels-at-tech-conferences/266837/&#34;&gt;men pledging to not speak unless there‚Äôs a satisfactory representation of women&lt;/a&gt; is helpful, because it‚Äôs telling the organisers that diversity is important to them, and that you believe the current lineup isn‚Äôt representative of a fair speaker selection process.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;acknowledging-whats-going-on&#34;&gt;Acknowledging what‚Äôs going on&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs not always a problem if organisers used a fair process and it still resulted in an all white male lineup. The important part is that they acknowledge there‚Äôs a problem and try to explain &lt;em&gt;why&lt;/em&gt;. We all know that there‚Äôs not as many women in the industry as men, what we want to know is that people are trying to improve upon the situation, rather than promoting an environment where minorities don‚Äôt feel comfortable. Without even acknowledging that a problem exists, the imbalance in the industry will inevitably continue.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;standing-up&#34;&gt;Standing up&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Campaigning for diversity is the final controversy. It‚Äôs not a fun topic to discuss, and people are very easily hurt if they feel as though they‚Äôre being attacked or accused of gender discrimination. Unfortunately this results in all sorts of people reacting in ways that aim to shut up those who are trying to address the imbalance:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1.Both men and women have said that men‚Äôs opinions on the matter aren‚Äôt as valid as women‚Äôs opinions. This is sad. While men may not have been able to experience the bias against women first-hand, that shouldn‚Äôt mean that they‚Äôre not allowed to fight for the equality that they believe in.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A great analogy from Martin Pilkington ‚Äú‚Ä¶But you‚Äôre not allowed to speak out on women‚Äôs rights as you‚Äôre not a woman! Nor animal rights as you‚Äôre not a pigeon!‚Äù (&lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/pilky/status/294468887246938115&#34;&gt;https://twitter.com/pilky/status/294468887246938115&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;2.¬†I‚Äôve seen a few women on Twitter imply that it‚Äôs not a problem because they haven‚Äôt had bad experiences themselves. This is the camp I used to fall into. Because it wasn‚Äôt affecting me, I didn‚Äôt want to draw negative attention to myself. It‚Äôs ok if you haven‚Äôt experienced something and so you feel uncomfortable standing up for it, but to deny that something exists because it hasn‚Äôt affected you seems very self-centred.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;3&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;This is the one that I had feared for so long, and it finally happened to me a couple of weeks ago:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúWell she certainly wasn‚Äôt a ‚Äòtoken girl‚Äô at our second event, but she appears to want to be branded as one‚Äù (&lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/leydon/status/294457218114408448&#34;&gt;https://twitter.com/leydon/status/294457218114408448&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;4&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The best way to shut women up about equal rights is to suggest that they‚Äôre only doing it for selfish reasons.*&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;nobody-wants-to-be-the-token-speaker&#34;&gt;Nobody wants to be the token speaker&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I enjoy speaking occasionally, but I‚Äôm really more of a fan of attending conferences. I don‚Äôt want token women speakers to exist, let alone have people suggest that I am one, and that I was only asked to speak to fulfil a quota.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;keeping-on-standing-up&#34;&gt;Keeping on standing up&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;im-still-going-to-fight-this-one-out-though-i-want-to-make-the-industry-a-more-diverse-interesting-and-inviting-place-and-i-want-to-set-a-good-example-for-those-that-come-after-usa-loveletter-a-loveletter-i-know-that-im-quite-a-confident-person-and-i-feel-like-im-in-a-better-position-to-stand-up-for-us-than-many-others-and-i-dont-want-to-waste-my-opportunity-to-do-so&#34;&gt;I‚Äôm still going to fight this one out, though. I want to make the industry a more diverse, interesting and inviting place, and I want to &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/a-loveletter/&#34; title=&#34;A loveletter&#34;&gt;set a good example for those that come after us&lt;/a&gt;. I know that I‚Äôm quite a confident person, and I feel like I‚Äôm in a better position to stand up for us than many others, and I don‚Äôt want to waste my opportunity to do so.&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;note&#34;&gt;Note&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are people who write about this subject in a far more analytical, less emotional, way. If you want to know more, I particularly recommend Aral Balkan‚Äôs, Faruk Ate≈ü‚Äôs and Sara Wachter-Boettcher‚Äôs¬†posts. I‚Äôve included some that I‚Äôve found very useful below:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://alistapart.com/article/universal-design-irl&#34;&gt;Universal Design IRL&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://farukat.es/journal/2012/11/673-problem-slate-white-male-speakers&#34;&gt;The Problem with a Slate of White, Male Speakers&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://aralbalkan.com/notes/on-false-dichotomies-and-diversity/&#34;&gt;On false dichotomies and diversity&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://aralbalkan.com/notes/stop-staring-at-my-willy-please/&#34;&gt;Stop staring at my willy, please&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://aralbalkan.com/notes/diversity-equality-toxicity-etc/&#34;&gt;Diversity, equality, toxicity, etc&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
