	&lt;/div&gt;
	&lt;div class=&#34;comment-entry&#34;&gt;
		Traditionally, I‚Äôve always leaned towards the school of thought that says ‚ÄúThe population is evenly split along gender lines, women are just as talented as men, therefore the number of women in the industry/on boards of directors/speaking at conferences should automatically balance themselves, without any need to do anything about it.‚Äù That works well enough in theory, but if, as seems to be the case, it isn‚Äôt balancing well, then I‚Äôm happy to do what I can to adjust the situation. For reasons that I don‚Äôt entirely understand, having not experienced them myself, (some) women seem to need, or at least appreciate, female role models. Therefore, it seems to me that for the tech industry (conference speakers etc) to balance properly, we first need to reach a critical mass of female role models. If this is something that can only be achieved by actively considering the gender of speakers, then so be it.
&lt;p&gt;Regarding your point about male views not being as valid as female ones: I think a lot of men (myself included) feel that expressing opinions on this subject is a little bit like a rich MP talking about what life is like for the poor. Many of us would quite like to take more of a stand on the issue, but I think we need to be invited to do so by women first. Otherwise we feel like we‚Äôre barging in on a conversation of which we‚Äôre not currently a part.
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;ul class=&#34;children&#34;&gt;
&lt;li class=&#34;comment even depth-2&#34; id=&#34;li-comment-473&#34;&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;comment-author vcard&#34;&gt;
&lt;img alt=&#39;&#39; src=&#39;https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/c36b48f5546f3977336c4e7f2f33771a?s=72&amp;amp;d=mm&amp;amp;r=g&#39; srcset=&#39;https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/c36b48f5546f3977336c4e7f2f33771a?s=144&amp;amp;d=mm&amp;amp;r=g 2x&#39; class=&#39;avatar avatar-72 photo&#39; height=&#39;72&#39; width=&#39;72&#39; /&gt;&lt;cite class=&#34;fn&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#39;http://www.sophiedennis.co.uk&#39; rel=&#39;external nofollow&#39; class=&#39;url&#39;&gt;Sophie Dennis&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/cite&gt;
&lt;aside class=&#34;comment-meta commentmetadata&#34;&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#comment-473&#34;&gt;&lt;time datetime=&#34;2013-02-05T11:50:45+00:00&#34; pubdate class=&#34;published&#34;&gt;
at &lt;span class=&#34;hours&#34;&gt;11:50am&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;comment-entry&#34;&gt;
Mark, please do speak up. We need all the good men like yourself to take a stand on this ‚Äì; otherwise we‚Äôre too easily dismissed in some quarters as ‚Äúthose shrill women‚Äù.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I agree with Amber that it‚Äôs easy to be insulated from this even as a woman. I‚Äôve never been threatened or publicly insulted like many women I hear from. To be honest I‚Äôm fairly thick-skinned and when I‚Äôm aware of sexist behaviour towards myself, tend just to find it hilarious.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs something, as you can imagine, that Andy and I are grappling with with [Digpen](&lt;a href=&#34;http://digpen.com&#34;&gt;http://digpen.com&lt;/a&gt;&amp;quot; rel=&amp;ldquo;nofollow). Part of me can‚Äôt imagine anyone behaving like this at one of our conferences. I‚Äôm tempted to say that the atmosphere here in the South West is quite different, and we‚Äôre wary of making a big deal of ‚Äúzero tolerance‚Äù in case that makes people think we &lt;em&gt;do&lt;/em&gt; have a problem. At the same time, we want to make it clear that if there is ever this kind of behaviour at a Digpen event, or we hear of anyone treating our speakers badly (whatever their gender), we won‚Äôt stand for it.
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;ul class=&#34;children&#34;&gt;
&lt;li class=&#34;comment odd alt depth-3&#34; id=&#34;li-comment-475&#34;&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;comment-author vcard&#34;&gt;
&lt;img alt=&#39;&#39; src=&#39;https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/18592fc8bad8f92136390f52303ee29c?s=72&amp;amp;d=mm&amp;amp;r=g&#39; srcset=&#39;https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/18592fc8bad8f92136390f52303ee29c?s=144&amp;amp;d=mm&amp;amp;r=g 2x&#39; class=&#39;avatar avatar-72 photo&#39; height=&#39;72&#39; width=&#39;72&#39; /&gt;&lt;cite class=&#34;fn&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#39;http://markglover.co.uk&#39; rel=&#39;external nofollow&#39; class=&#39;url&#39;&gt;Mark Glover&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/cite&gt;
&lt;aside class=&#34;comment-meta commentmetadata&#34;&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#comment-475&#34;&gt;&lt;time datetime=&#34;2013-02-05T15:55:32+00:00&#34; pubdate class=&#34;published&#34;&gt;
at &lt;span class=&#34;hours&#34;&gt;15:55pm&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;comment-entry&#34;&gt;
As you can imagine, Sophie, I‚Äôve been thinking a lot about DigPen in this context, not least because it forms the bulk of my recent conference experience. I‚Äôve certainly never witnessed any sexism there, and I wonder if that is down to the crowd or the history of the event. Obviously DigPen has never set out to be female-orientated, but between being founded by Frankie and now steered by you, it‚Äôs always had a strong female presence on the stage. I have two ideas about why this may have made a difference. 1) An event that has a strong female presence from the outset might be less likely to attract the sort of men who don‚Äôt respect and value women in technology, and 2) (more importantly) the presence of women standing on that stage from day one has provided exactly the sort of role model for women that I was talking about above. This may have given other women confidence to both attend and speak at the events, without worrying that they won‚Äôt be received well. Of course it could simply be that everyone connected to DigPen is just so damn lovely ;-)
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
