	&lt;div class=&#34;comment-entry&#34;&gt;
		Thanks for the interesting and thoughtful post. I think you make some good points about criticism and context. It is not just about our personal context. It is also our culture, our society and so on. People forget or don‚Äôt realise that knowledge they take for granted is often not there in other people. 
&lt;p&gt;Also, I think you provide a good example of some of what I don‚Äôt like about Twitter.
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/we-read-with-our-own-contexts/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòWe read with our own contexts‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm speaking at the &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.meetup.com/London-WordPress/events/81910532/&#34;&gt;WordPress London January meetup on the 17th of January 2013&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve been using WordPress for years, for my own site and for client sites, and I really love it. I had absolutely no idea what to talk about though. I tend to create custom themes for clients, but these are very different from themes designed for use by many different sites, and so I wasn‚Äôt sure whether my experience would be relevant to many people. I also don‚Äôt feel very confident speaking about code.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;a-mad-idea&#34;&gt;A mad idea&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thinking about the different things I do that are related to WordPress, I decided to go very niche. &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/project/wordpress-admin-icons/&#34; title=&#34;WordPress Admin Icons&#34;&gt;WordPress admin icons&lt;/a&gt; are something I‚Äôve been doing a lot of lately, and they combine the skills of icon design with the skills of fitting icons in with an existing set. My talk is going to be:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;designing-wordpress-admin-icons&#34;&gt;Designing WordPress Admin Icons&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The WordPress admin has really evolved into something lovely over the last few years. So when you create plugins and custom post types, you want custom icons that feel at home in the interface. Laura is going to discuss her top tips for creating icons, and attempt to live-design a WordPress admin icon to show you step-by-step how she does it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;live-designingeek&#34;&gt;Live-designing‚Ä¶eek&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It might go all horribly wrong, but I thought the best way to describe how I design these icons isn‚Äôt just to show pictures, but to show the process. It‚Äôs often tricky to describe our processes as so many of the steps we do have become second-nature, we barely think about what we‚Äôre doing. So &lt;em&gt;hopefully&lt;/em&gt;, designing live will help me do a better job of explaining the tools and techniques that I use.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;id-love-to-see-you-there&#34;&gt;I‚Äôd love to see you there!&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you‚Äôre going to be there, do say hello! At the moment &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.meetup.com/London-WordPress/events/81910532/&#34;&gt;it looks as though there‚Äôs no space left&lt;/a&gt;, but more spots will open up before the event.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;2-comments&#34;&gt;2 comments&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ol class=&#34;commentlist&#34;&gt;
			&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/speaking-at-the-wordpress-london-january-meetup/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòSpeaking at the WordPress London January meetup‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For the last few years, I‚Äôve been working with a great team of people on &lt;a href=&#34;https://itunes.apple.com/app/bardowl/id492667930?ls=1&amp;amp;mt=8&#34;&gt;our iPhone app&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;http://bardowl.com&#34;&gt;Bardowl&lt;/a&gt;, an app for streaming unlimited audiobooks for ¬£9.99 a month (think Spotify but for audiobooks.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs not been a quick and easy. Getting publishers to come round to the idea, and securing good audiobooks, has been a lengthy process but we‚Äôve been lucky to have people who really know what they‚Äôre talking about behind the scenes. Our &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/bookmeister&#34;&gt;CEO, Chris Book&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/neilp33l&#34;&gt;CTO, Neil Chapman&lt;/a&gt;, have bootstrapped the business and have worked incredibly hard, taking a big risk, because they really believe in bringing good audiobooks to the iPhone without massive subscription costs or limited listening choices. They‚Äôre the reason I was first interested in being involved, and the reason I‚Äôve stuck at it for so long.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;why-only-blog-about-it-now&#34;&gt;Why only blog about it now?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I wanted to wait until there was a version of the app that you‚Äôd want to try. Previously, we launched with ‚Äòbusiness books.‚Äô These are wonderful if you‚Äôre into management techniques, deals, finances and all these audiobooks that I find, quite honestly, dull.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;now-the-catalogue-has-got-so-much-awesome&#34;&gt;Now the catalogue has got so much awesome&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But now, the catalogue has some serious awesome with biographies and memoirs, childrens books, classic, contemporary and modern fiction, non-fiction, poetry and drama. Roald Dahl‚Äôs Revolting Rhymes, Cormac McCarthy‚Äôs No Country For Old Men, loads of Dickens and Sherlock Holmes. I really think you‚Äôll like it. Oh yes, and you can &lt;a href=&#34;https://itunes.apple.com/app/bardowl/id492667930?ls=1&amp;amp;mt=8&#34;&gt;try it for free for 7 days&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;what-have-i-done-then&#34;&gt;What have I done then?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I am the sole designer. I do all the design; branding, app design and web design/development. It‚Äôs really the first product I‚Äôve ever worked with, and I enjoy having something I get to stick with and iterate over time. I‚Äôm still not sure if I‚Äôd want to do this full time, I really love the variety that comes with client work, but it‚Äôs very rewarding feeling like you‚Äôre constantly improving one product.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;working-for-almost-free&#34;&gt;Working for almost-free&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I also work almost solely for a small share (I‚Äôve had a few payments for work when we had some investment.) Since I started time-tracking the project in March 2010, I‚Äôve put 430 hours into the project, around half of that being on the website, which has had three or four full redesigns. This working for almost-free is definitely not something I would do again, which I will elaborate on below.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;learning&#34;&gt;Learning&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs been a complete learning experience. It was my first app design work, I created the logo long before I started working professionally as a designer, and I‚Äôve never worked as part of a startup before, in fact I‚Äôve never really worked as part of another company before (as a designer.) Starting before I graduated from university, it‚Äôs been a project that has spanned the whole of my freelance/professional career. As I‚Äôve learned new things, I‚Äôve been able to experiment, and put my new knowledge straight into the app and the website. It was my first mobile website design (pre-‚ÄúResponsive Web Design‚Äù,) my first foray into web fonts, my first ‚ÄúResponsive Web Design‚Äù and my first experience with CSS pre-processors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;designing-and-developing&#34;&gt;Designing and developing&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve learned a huge amount about designing for apps. Unlike designing for the web, where I usually write the markup and sometimes the code, I can‚Äôt develop iOS apps. I don‚Äôt think this is a good thing, it really emphasises why I think that you must be able to write markup in order to design for the web. Designing for iOS apps, with fairly minimal knowledge of the development process is &lt;em&gt;really hard&lt;/em&gt;. I make a complete pain out of myself, constantly asking &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/kgutteridge&#34;&gt;Kieran&lt;/a&gt; questions about how things work, what‚Äôs possible, what‚Äôs native, and what would be easiest to create from a development point-of-view.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While I‚Äôve learned loads from Kieran, I still want to know more about the development process. In the new year, I‚Äôve resolved to attend &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/aral&#34;&gt;Aral Balkan&lt;/a&gt;‚Äòs &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.moderniosdevelopment.com/&#34;&gt;Modern iOS Development Workshop&lt;/a&gt; (I‚Äôve heard so many good things.) But I don‚Äôt really see myself developing apps for a living, I find programming very difficult and not terribly rewarding, I just think my design decisions can be more well-informed as a result.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;designing-for-free&#34;&gt;Designing for free&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Above I said I wouldn‚Äôt work for free (shares) again. As a general rule, I wouldn‚Äôt recommend it, it‚Äôs a huge risk and chances are you‚Äôll never make a return on the hours you put into the project.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, my specific reason I wouldn‚Äôt work for free is that I believe people can often struggle to understand and appreciate the value in design if they‚Äôre not paying for it. They‚Äôve not got an interest in getting the best value for money, so they don‚Äôt necessarily feel as though they should listen to what you say. In a way, the developer will always have the final say, as whatever they make is what gets released.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When you‚Äôve worked for free, and you‚Äôve put so much time and effort into a project, you‚Äôre less likely to leave. The more time you spend, the more reluctant you‚Äôll be to leave that all behind. It‚Äôs like the &lt;a href=&#34;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stockholm_syndrome&#34;&gt;Stockholm Syndrome&lt;/a&gt; of working for free. I still completely believe in Bardowl as a concept, and I have a huge amount of respect and love for our CEO and CTO, and that‚Äôs why I persist in trying to make my app design live up to the idea, but I‚Äôd be lying if I said I didn‚Äôt have frustrated times where a loss of control and startup politics infuriated me.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;working-with-good-people&#34;&gt;Working with good people&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Despite the occasional hiccups, I‚Äôve found working with Bardowl immensely rewarding. There‚Äôs so much to be said about working for people who really believe and care about what they‚Äôre doing. It‚Äôs not just about doing design and development right, or business right, but about working with people right. Our CEO Chris Book is an example of somebody who cares about the people he works with. His role as CEO has often mean placating, convincing and cajoling, but he doesn‚Äôt just do this as a means to getting his app finished, he genuinely believes in providing value for those working on the project. And doing it all with honesty and transparency. Honesty and transparency are massively underrated.&lt;/p&gt;
