&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/bardowl-the-big-one/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòBardowl: The Big One‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve posted a &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.ubelly.com/2012/12/reinvention-and-building-ourselves-build-2012/&#34;&gt;writeup of Build conference 2012 on ubelly&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Oddly, I‚Äôve not found any other writeups from Build, which may be because (as I mention in my post) the talks weren‚Äôt those sound-bite talks that give quick take away tips. If anyone does come across any, please point me in the right direction as I‚Äôd love to see how other people approached the wide-ranging stories!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/reinvention-and-building-ourselves-build-2012/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòReinvention and Building Ourselves ‚Äî Build 2012‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yesterday was &lt;a href=&#34;http://viewportindustries.com/events/insites-the-xmas-special/&#34;&gt;Insites: The Xmas Special&lt;/a&gt;, a brilliant event put on by the lovely &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/keirwhitaker&#34;&gt;Keir Whitaker&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/elliotjaystocks&#34;&gt;Elliot Jay Stocks&lt;/a&gt;. After being well fed, everybody in the room gave a six minute(ish) talk about something they‚Äôve learned in 2012.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It was a personal, open and incredibly meaningful set of talks. There were no slides, and nobody in the room was sat behind a laptop or Twitter. The conversations that ensued afterwards were greater than anything you‚Äôd get at any big conference. We had all shared our experiences equally and honestly. As &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/rachelandrew&#34;&gt;Rachel Andrew&lt;/a&gt; put so well, it was almost group therapy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One of the rules of the day was that what happened in the School Of Life stayed in the School Of Life, so far be it for me to report the personal stories of other people. However, I‚Äôm happy to share what I spoke about, so I thought I‚Äôd share it here‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;not-picking-sides&#34;&gt;Not picking sides&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm the eldest of five children in my family. It‚Äôs a big family and none of us are shy. However, I‚Äôm usually referred to as the ‚Äúsensible one‚Äù or the ‚Äúcalm one‚Äù. I‚Äôm all about diplomacy and trying to keep the peace if there‚Äôs any upset or argyments. It‚Äôs not that I‚Äôm afraid of conflict, I think arguments can be healthy and constructive, but I really don‚Äôt like picking sides.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Yet for so many years I didn‚Äôt take this approach when I was working on the web. CSS layouts were good, tables were bad. Semantic web was good, Flash was bad. To me, these were facts and exceptions were begrudgingly accepted as freak edge-cases.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When there‚Äôs so much to learn on the web, it‚Äôs much easier to follow than to lead, or even just make up your own mind. As humans we seem to be drawn to polarity; picking sides. Which football team do you support? Which political party are you aligned to? Which religion do you believe in? But it‚Äôs such an unhelpful way to live. Polarity lacks subtlety, it leads to blind acceptance of everything you‚Äôre told.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you think about it in terms of politics, you feel forced to &lt;a href=&#34;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toe_the_line&#34;&gt;toe the party line&lt;/a&gt;. This kind of politics is damaging in itself; if everyone in a group is made to believe exactly the same thing, unquestioningly, it‚Äôs very hard to accept any new ideas or change your mind. You can‚Äôt back-track. And because you feel as though you must ‚Äústick to your side‚Äù, you blindly defend you side‚Äôs beliefs at a risk to your own integrity.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;integrity&#34;&gt;Integrity&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Integrity is something that has always meant a lot to me. But I feel like sometimes I‚Äôve been guilty of risking my own integrity in order to fit in. It‚Äôs hard to go against the group, nobody wants to feel like an outsider.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But life‚Äôs too short to do things that don‚Äôt make you feel proud. Of course we all do &lt;em&gt;those&lt;/em&gt; projects that are good for cashflow or good for your profile, and hopefully these don‚Äôt run completely contrary to your personal beliefs, but even if we can own a tiny little part of these projects; do something good and something that we‚Äôre proud of, we can make that project worthwhile in terms of our integrity.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We need to continually question what we‚Äôre doing and why we bother. I think I‚Äôm right in saying that most of what we do isn‚Äôt just ‚Äúa job.‚Äù We do this because we care and we want to make better experiences for everyone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;one-comment&#34;&gt;One comment&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ol class=&#34;commentlist&#34;&gt;
	&lt;li class=&#34;comment even thread-even depth-1&#34; id=&#34;li-comment-407&#34;&gt;
			&lt;div class=&#34;comment-author vcard&#34;&gt;
			&lt;img alt=&#39;&#39; src=&#39;https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/7c77bb634e33febe9e2e9a2745732ca3?s=72&amp;amp;d=mm&amp;amp;r=g&#39; srcset=&#39;https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/7c77bb634e33febe9e2e9a2745732ca3?s=144&amp;amp;d=mm&amp;amp;r=g 2x&#39; class=&#39;avatar avatar-72 photo&#39; height=&#39;72&#39; width=&#39;72&#39; /&gt;&lt;cite class=&#34;fn&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#39;http://twitter.com/danblundell&#39; rel=&#39;external nofollow&#39; class=&#39;url&#39;&gt;Dan Blundell&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/cite&gt;
				&lt;aside class=&#34;comment-meta commentmetadata&#34;&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#comment-407&#34;&gt;&lt;time datetime=&#34;2012-12-04T09:25:28+00:00&#34; pubdate class=&#34;published&#34;&gt;
		 at &lt;span class=&#34;hours&#34;&gt;09:25am&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/aside&gt;
	&lt;/div&gt;
	&lt;div class=&#34;comment-entry&#34;&gt;
		‚ÄúWe need to continually question what we‚Äôre doing and why we bother. I think I‚Äôm right in saying that most of what we do isn‚Äôt just ‚Äúa job.‚Äù We do this because we care and we want to make better experiences for everyone.‚Äù ‚Äì; This just nailed exactly why I‚Äôm feeling the way I am at the minute, good to know that there‚Äôs others that feel the same way! 
&lt;p&gt;It can be really difficult when you‚Äôre surrounded by people that consider a job simply a job but I whole heartedly agree, if you can do even one tiny thing that you‚Äôre proud of, even in the toughest of projects, you can stay happy because our work means something.
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/insites-xmas-specialintegrity-and-polarity/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòInsites Xmas Special‚ÄîIntegrity and Polarity‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;or-the-things-you-think-are-common-knowledge-but-really-they-arent&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Or&lt;/em&gt; The things you think are common knowledge but really they aren‚Äôt.&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://shoptalkshow.com/episodes/040-with-laura-kalbag/&#34;&gt;I was on the ShopTalk show&lt;/a&gt;¬†a few weeks ago, and a few people have asked me what I meant when I said ‚Äú&lt;code&gt;display: none;&lt;/code&gt; naughties.‚Äù I foolishly thought that people would understand what I meant, (and I‚Äôll come to that later) so I thought I‚Äôd better explain myself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;display-none-in-responsive-web-design&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;display: none;&lt;/code&gt; in responsive web design&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When we‚Äôre &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.alistapart.com/articles/responsive-web-design&#34;&gt;changing out layouts based on viewport sizes, using media queries&lt;/a&gt;, we tend to switch page elements about a bit. We might make our images display one-on-top-of-the-other for narrower layouts, we might make our text super big to take advantage of bigger spaces.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There can be a lot of content on one web page, and often there‚Äôs a temptation to hide some of it on narrower viewports. This walks hand-in-hand with the assumptions that narrow viewports are mobile devices and people using mobile devices are roving the planet using the web ‚Äòon the go.‚Äô&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;assumptions&#34;&gt;Assumptions&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But those assumptions are exactly that, you‚Äôre just &lt;em&gt;assuming&lt;/em&gt; that‚Äôs what the user is doing, you‚Äôre not basing that on real research or user testing. Why are you hiding so much of your content if you‚Äôre assuming it‚Äôs also useful to those browsing your site with a wider viewport?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;dont-be-lazy&#34;&gt;Don‚Äôt be lazy&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Just hiding content is a lazy design solution. Yes, it‚Äôs hard designing for smaller screens, but maybe that will help you ensure that every little piece of content you‚Äôre putting on that site is worthwhile.¬†Responsive design should be about rearranging, not changing, your page elements.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;and-then-youre-actually-just-loading-it-anyway&#34;&gt;And then you‚Äôre actually just loading it anyway‚Ä¶&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When you‚Äôre putting content into your page, and &lt;em&gt;then&lt;/em&gt; hiding it with CSS, it‚Äôs still there, it‚Äôs just not visible. So if you‚Äôre using this ‚Äòtechnique‚Äô across your site in numerous places, you‚Äôre likely taking a performance hit. And potentially, for narrower viewports/possible mobile devices, in the one place that a slow-loading page is likely to irritate a user. It‚Äôs just not worth that risk.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;changing-the-display-not-hiding-the-display&#34;&gt;Changing the display, not hiding the display&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One solution I‚Äôve been using is changing the display of the content. It is a real problem that CSS can‚Äôt easily manipulate all types of content into a readable fashion on all devices. This is particularly true for navigation that needs to be displayed in a significantly different way, and often tables need to be reinterpreted into a more digestible format for narrow viewports. And in these cases, javascript can be your friend.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;mobile-first&#34;&gt;Mobile first&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I always start mobile first, that‚Äôs not just in markup, it‚Äôs in content too. We don‚Äôt want to load up unnecessary HTML that creates performance problems, or javascript that may not working consistently on mobile devices.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If I‚Äôve got a data table, and I think it would be better off displayed as a list of data, I would write the list of data into the HTML. This way it‚Äôll load quickly, and those without javascript (or enough bandwidth to load javascript) will get a decent experience.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;progressively-enhancing-with-javascript&#34;&gt;Progressively enhancing with javascript&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Then, I would use media queries, or some kind of clever javascript, to load in the fancy content for particular viewport widths. I‚Äôve done this to load in tables of data, replacing data lists, and also for navigation, replacing a vertical list of links with a show/hide button that reveals the menu when tapped (as on this site.) None of this requires &lt;code&gt;display: none;&lt;/code&gt;. No markup is wasted.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;edit-accessibility&#34;&gt;[Edit]: Accessibility&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-good-steve-marshallhttptwittercomstevemarshall-has-pointed-out-that-there-are-also-accessbility-issues-related-to-display-none-i-didnt-want-to-cover-too-much-in-the-post-but-in-case-you-want-to-know-more-about-that-too-i-recommend-aaron-gustafsons-now-you-see-me-on-a-list-aparthttpwwwalistapartcomarticlesnow-you-see-me-and-chris-coyiers-places-its-tempting-to-use-display-none-but-dont-on-css-trickshttpcss-trickscomplaces-its-tempting-to-use-display-none-but-dont-edit&#34;&gt;The good &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/SteveMarshall&#34;&gt;Steve Marshall&lt;/a&gt; has pointed out that there are also accessbility issues related to &lt;code&gt;display: none;&lt;/code&gt;. I didn‚Äôt want to cover too much in the post, but in case you want to know more about that too, I recommend &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.alistapart.com/articles/now-you-see-me/&#34;&gt;Aaron Gustafson‚Äôs ‚ÄòNow You See Me‚Äô on A List Apart&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;http://css-tricks.com/places-its-tempting-to-use-display-none-but-dont/&#34;&gt;Chris Coyier‚Äôs ‚ÄòPlaces It‚Äôs Tempting To Use Display: None; But Don‚Äôt on CSS Tricks&lt;/a&gt;. [/edit]&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;writing-about-markup&#34;&gt;Writing about markup&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm a little bit scared of writing about markup. I‚Äôm sure there are loads of front-end developers out there who know a huge amount more than me, and I‚Äôm worried I‚Äôll get it wrong or make myself look stupid.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I also shy away from writing about the ‚Äòeasy‚Äô stuff. This post about &lt;code&gt;display: none;&lt;/code&gt; is a fairly simple principle and I really don‚Äôt want to patronise anyone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;people-do-want-to-hear-about-the-simple-stuff&#34;&gt;People do want to hear about the ‚Äòsimple‚Äô stuff&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Making these assumptions about it being a simple principle, and that everybody would know about it already, was daft. I was quickly proved wrong when people started asking me about it and then I realised how silly it was to think that we all have the same sources of information.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;scattered-learning&#34;&gt;Scattered learning&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The web is a big and varied place. To assume that someone else has read something just because you‚Äôve read it is foolish. How do we learn about these resources? When do we all decide that we‚Äôre all going to read these particular sites and articles so that we‚Äôre all equally informed?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Even on Twitter, the resources we hear from, and learn from, are wildly different. We may follow completely different individuals and so the resources we learn from are curated by these individuals, and these may not ever crossover. Even if we do follow the same people on Twitter, noone can be expected to read every tweet, and inevitably you‚Äôll miss some, and then you may not know about this other new thing that everybody else has been doing for years.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;where-i-get-to-the-point&#34;&gt;Where I get to the point‚Ä¶&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The point I‚Äôm trying to make is that we shouldn‚Äôt be fearful of writing about what we know. Even if you write from the most basic point of view, about something which has been ‚Äòaround for ages‚Äô, you‚Äôll likely be saying something new to someone. They might be new to the industry, you might just be filling in the holes in someone‚Äôs knowledge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Every week I have a revelation on app.net or Twitter where I wonder how I didn‚Äôt know about this old technique or tool before‚Ä¶ but we can‚Äôt be expected to keep up with everything. I hope this post does that for some people. It‚Äôs good to share what we know. You needn‚Äôt be the first, you‚Äôll just help if you‚Äôre the first that somebody finds.&lt;/p&gt;
