	&lt;div class=&#34;comment-entry&#34;&gt;
		I haven‚Äôt actually been using `display: none;` very often on its own. I‚Äôve mainly used JavaScript to hide elements I manipulate through a situational `.hide` class. I‚Äôve gotten into a habit of using temporary classes for states to applied through JavaScript. This way, if something effs up, I won‚Äôt be hiding critical information from the user. 
&lt;p&gt;If I ever find I‚Äôm hiding an element indefinitely, it usually means it‚Äôs time to figure out if it‚Äôs needed at all. And I liked your last point over not being afraid to contribute something to the pool of knowledge. My reluctance to write blog posts comes from the fact that I‚Äôm entirely self-taught, so I have a tendency to assume everything I know IS common knowledge and I have nothing to add. I may have to rethink that.
