&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://panic.com/coda/&#34;&gt;Coda&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt; My development text editor of choice. It has some handy features and is prettier than a plain text editor. I don‚Äôt really use the FTP very much so sometimes wonder if I should try something new.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;**&lt;a href=&#34;http://mac.github.com/&#34;&gt;GitHub For Mac&lt;/a&gt;.¬†**The main way I interact with GitHub. I‚Äôm still a little bit fearful of Terminal, so GitHub For Mac provides me with an interface that helps me understand what I‚Äôm really doing with Git.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;**&lt;a href=&#34;http://incident57.com/codekit/&#34;&gt;Codekit&lt;/a&gt;.¬†**A brilliant brilliant app for compiling pre-processors (and other things.) I use it with Sass which I write in Coda and commit in GitHub for Mac. Dream team.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.mamp.info/en/mamp-pro/index.html&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;MAMP Pro&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. Makes managing your local server environment (especially if you‚Äôre working with virtual machines) a lot easier. I use the Pro version because the the non-pro version is intimidating.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://code.google.com/p/snippely/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Snippely&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. I changed the dock icon because the original scissors icon was too ugly! A code snippet app where I keep all the super-repetitive stuff like CSS resets and WordPress loops.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.pixa-app.com/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pixa&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. A new app I‚Äôm trying out for organising all the ‚Äòresources‚Äô folders I have for files like icons. So far it‚Äôs pretty nice.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.bohemiancoding.com/sketch/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sketch&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. The vector graphics app (see above!)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.pixelmator.com/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pixelmator&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. The photo editing app (see above!)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;[&lt;strong&gt;Photoshop&lt;/strong&gt;](&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.photoshop.com/products/photoshop%22&#34;&gt;http://www.photoshop.com/products/photoshop&amp;quot;&lt;/a&gt; rel=&amp;ldquo;nofollow). Because even if I don‚Äôt want to use it, I still have to use it for legacy files and working with other developers.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.adobe.com/products/illustrator.html&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Illustrator&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. As above, I only use Illustrator for legacy files. And saving vector files in formats that I can open in Sketch.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://panic.com/transmit/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Transmit&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. I use Transmit occasionally for FTP and SSH, but more as a Finder for hidden files!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.bohemiancoding.com/fontcase/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fontcase&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. A great app for activating and organising your fonts. Tagging and collections makes it easy to organise in a way that suits you.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.apple.com/itunes/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;iTunes.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;em&gt;Mac OSX default&lt;/em&gt;)¬†Like most people, I don‚Äôt really like using iTunes. But I love CDs (yeah, so what? I‚Äôm old-school) and obtaining music in a legal way. iTunes makes this easy enough.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.spotify.com/uk/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Spotify.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; For when I want to listen to something new, or something that‚Äôs too embarrassing to buy‚Ä¶ ;)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://tapbots.com/software/tweetbot/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tweetbot.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; I believe in paying for good apps. Tweetbot has so many features and makes multi-column use of Twitter a delight.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://wedge.natestedman.com/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wedge.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; One of the more polished &lt;a href=&#34;https://join.app.net/&#34;&gt;app.net&lt;/a&gt; apps for desktop.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://agilebits.com/onepassword&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1Password.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; The only way I‚Äôll ever be able to have secure passwords is by having an app that acts as my memory for all those secure passwords. 1Password is great, and syncs to an iPhone version.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://imageoptim.com/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ImageOptim&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. Can usually cut at least 15% off an image‚Äôs size without losing quality. Useful for anything you‚Äôre putting on the web, and doubly-useful if the graphics apps you‚Äôre working with don‚Äôt have a Save For Web functionality.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;we-need-to-question-our-tools&#34;&gt;We need to question our tools&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄòIndustry standard‚Äô and ‚Äònot worth paying for‚Äô are both blights on our industry. Everybody has different needs and different budgets. The apps I use might not be right for you, I‚Äôm not telling you that you must use them, and you shouldn‚Äôt do that either.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If we keep an open mind, a willingness to try new apps that might better suit our workflows, and the understanding that a good app is worth buying, maybe we‚Äôll finally get a bit closer to those dream apps that can solve all our problems.&lt;/p&gt;
