&lt;h2 id=&#34;programming-block&#34;&gt;Programming block&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm a bit scared of JavaScript. Since I started learning front-end development about seven years ago, I‚Äôve pretty much stayed away from it. That aside from some pretty dodgy jQuery where I can usually bodge something together but would never rely on it. I‚Äôve always said it‚Äôs because I wanted to be &lt;em&gt;really really&lt;/em&gt; good at HTML first, and &lt;strong&gt;then&lt;/strong&gt; CSS and &lt;strong&gt;then&lt;/strong&gt; JavaScript, but I somehow always stopped short of actually learning JavaScript properly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is because I was scared of it. I might be able to put together some basic PHP when working with WordPress, but I really wouldn‚Äôt consider myself a programmer. The less that the code I‚Äôm writing has an instant visual output, the more I get confused by it. I‚Äôve tried to learn all sorts of different languages but they always go in one ear and out the other. I had just settled for knowing enough to be able to know what the right solution should be and finding someone clever to help me.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;theres-a-lot-of-javascript-on-the-web&#34;&gt;There‚Äôs a lot of JavaScript on the web&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The problem was, that in doing this, I was really limiting myself. There‚Äôs a lot of JavaScript on the web. Even if you‚Äôre not using it to do something fancy on a site, if you‚Äôre a modern developer using progressive enhancement then chances are you‚Äôre using some kind of shiv or polyfill that relies on JavaScript. It‚Äôs pretty hypocritical of me if I go around saying I don‚Äôt use HTML and CSS frameworks, because writing all my own markup from scratch means I understand every little bit of it, when I don‚Äôt really understand the shivs and polyfills I‚Äôm using to help me use elements of HTML5 and CSS3.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;creativejs-for-non-coders-workshop&#34;&gt;CreativeJS for non-coders workshop&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://seb.ly&#34;&gt;Seb Lee-Delisle&lt;/a&gt;¬†was putting on another couple of &lt;a href=&#34;http://seb.ly/training/&#34;&gt;workshops teaching CreativeJS&lt;/a&gt;. Everyone I‚Äôd known that had been to one of Seb‚Äôs workshops had said it was incredibly worthwhile and good fun. I didn‚Äôt have an excuse to put off learning JavaScript. And whilst I go to a lot of conferences, I‚Äôd not been to a proper two day workshop before so I wasn‚Äôt really sure what to expect.&lt;/p&gt;

