&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/six-months-of-the-fitbit-and-the-new-fitbit-aria/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòSix months of the Fitbit (and the new Fitbit Aria)‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve written &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.ubelly.com/2012/06/typography-and-the-web-at-ampersand-conference/&#34;&gt;a big old writeup for ubelly&lt;/a&gt; from my notes at &lt;a href=&#34;http://2012.ampersandconf.com/&#34;&gt;Ampersand conference&lt;/a&gt; earlier in the month.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This was an event I decided not to live-tweet, as the content is usually more involved and in-depth, making for a better big writeup and less tweetable quotes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.ubelly.com/2012/06/typography-and-the-web-at-ampersand-conference/&#34;&gt;Typography and the web at Ampersand conference&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/typography-and-the-web-at-ampersand-conference/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòTypography and the web at Ampersand Conference‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve been contemplating how designers can identify better with more mainstream users.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I had a thought last week. What if, by rejecting Facebook, I‚Äôm actually missing out on design patterns that are so influential on the mainstream user that it affects their perception on the rest of the web?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And the same goes for Google Chrome. I‚Äôve been going through a rebellious anti-Google phase, but now &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.theverge.com/2012/5/21/3033566/chrome-most-popular-browser-weekly-may-2012&#34;&gt;Chrome has taken over as the world‚Äôs most popular browser&lt;/a&gt;, am I making life harder for myself by developing sites in Safari first?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As designers (and in the creative and tech industries generally) I think we might err on the side of the hipster. We can start to reject brands and products because we‚Äôre ‚Äútoo cool¬†for that mainstream stuff the average user falls for‚Ä¶‚Äù Or maybe we‚Äôre just acutely aware of the downsides, hitches and ill-intentions web services might have because we work in the industry.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Could it be positive that we arrive at mainstream products, when we need to do research, with the fresh eye of a new user? Or are we tainted by the fact we know too much? We could be saving ourselves from being inspired by standards and conventions that might be poor, but are we better informed for knowing as many potential solutions to common problems as possible?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Well I think I‚Äôm going to try being more of a mainstream user. I want to understand the web better as other people see it. I‚Äôm switching to Google Chrome for now, and I‚Äôve signed up to Facebook again.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;id-say-ill-post-in-a-months-time-and-write-about-whether-ive-noticed-a-change-but-im-not-sure-itll-be-as-conscious-as-that-well-have-to-wait-and-see&#34;&gt;I‚Äôd say I‚Äôll post in a month‚Äôs time and write about whether I‚Äôve noticed a change, but I‚Äôm not sure it‚Äôll be as conscious as that. We‚Äôll have to wait and see‚Ä¶&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Note: throughout this post I keep saying ‚Äòmainstream.‚Äô This is because I feel that ‚Äòaverage‚Äô or ‚Äònormal‚Äô aren‚Äôt really the right words. I‚Äôm trying to talk about that majority of users who are consumers, rather than makers or builders, of the web.&lt;/p&gt;
