&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/insites-tour-brighton/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòInsites Tour Brighton‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I had ordered &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.abookapart.com/products/responsive-web-design&#34; title=&#34;Responsive Web Design on the A Book Apart store&#34;&gt;Responsive Web Design&lt;/a&gt;¬†by &lt;a href=&#34;http://ethanmarcotte.com/&#34;&gt;Ethan Marcotte&lt;/a&gt; as soon as it came out, but being at &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/digest-from-ampersand-conf/&#34; title=&#34;Notes from Ampersand conference ‚Äî My Digest&#34;&gt;Ampersand conference&lt;/a&gt;, and hearing &lt;em&gt;so many&lt;/em&gt; people recommend it, really spurred me to take a few hours out to get on and read it.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;portrait&#39;
      width=&#39;764&#39; height=&#39;1024&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/responsive-web-design/web_hud0f30c874602af04e0269a23b97dd9e1_181670_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/responsive-web-design/web_hud0f30c874602af04e0269a23b97dd9e1_181670_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/responsive-web-design/web.jpg 764w&#39;
      src=&#39;web.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Responsive Web Design by Ethan Marcotte&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;My copy of Responsive Web Design, already featuring a &#39;much used&#39; cover curl‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Responsive web design&lt;/strong&gt; is a term summarising design that has a flexibility allowing it to be optimised for different browsing experiences. This might be low levels of detail for mobile devices, big readable layouts for massive projector screens or dumbed-down CSS for old-fashioned browsers. I‚Äôm so sure that Responsive Web Design will be our bible for flexible web design for years to come.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The reason why I say ‚Äò&lt;em&gt;for years to come&lt;/em&gt;‚Äò is that Responsive Web Design doesn‚Äôt just furnish you with markup examples but &lt;em&gt;actual reasons&lt;/em&gt; to do it. Much like its predecessor, &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/html5-for-web-designers/&#34; title=&#34;HTML5 For Web Designers&#34;&gt;HTML5 For Web Designers&lt;/a&gt;¬†by Jeremy Keith, Ethan Marcotte walks you through how to think responsively, integrating flexibility into the design and development processes, and what might trip you up on the way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The book is split into five easily-digested chapters:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Our Responsive Web&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The Flexible Grid&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Flexible Images&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Media Queries&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Becoming Responsive&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These make for great reading if you can only fit one in at a time, but I reckon you could get the whole book read in front of a computer, trying examples as you go, in an afternoon.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I can tell you how useful this book is from how it‚Äôs helped me on a recent site design. I have always struggled with creating fluid CSS layouts using percentages. The maths has always boggled my mind and I tend to give it a go then give up when everything falls to bits as soon as I resize my browser window. The thorough explanation of using the magical formula,¬†&lt;strong&gt;target¬†√∑ context = result&lt;/strong&gt;,¬†had me working out percentage-based margins and paddings with very little effort. Now my designs can be more than just ‚Äòmobile version‚Äô and ‚Äòdesktop version‚Äô!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Part of what makes this book so valuable is the Bot Blog example site walkthrough. Being able to see how you can apply an original fixed-width design to a fluid-width site really helped me understand the restraints and opportunities created by working responsively.¬†The breakdown of media queries is incredibly handy, especially as they‚Äôre explained first from the position of starting with an average-width screen design, adapting down to small screens and up to larger screens using *max-width *rules, and then from the position of ‚Äòmobile first,‚Äô adding styles for gradually larger screens using *min-width *rules.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My favourite part of the book was where ‚ÄòMobile First‚Äô was introduced. This is the concept of developing first for a mobile browsing experience, then building upon that experience for bigger, more-advanced browsers. It‚Äôs pretty much a mobile-focused version of the progressive enhancement approach. It‚Äôs a great alternative to starting big and adjusting your CSS for small browsers as it means you‚Äôre not delivering huge long stylesheet files to phones that may have a slow or limited connection.¬†Quite a few developers on the more mobile-side of the web industry have been talking about ‚Äòmobile first‚Äô for years, ¬†but it‚Äôs great to see it really pulled into mainstream consideration.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Ethan Marcotte writes in a style that is casual but smart and funny in sweet, geeky way. His writing makes you feel like you‚Äôre learning from the easy-going class assistant rather than the boring teacher. It‚Äôs definitely made me opt to buy the two titles in between &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.abookapart.com/products/html5-for-web-designers&#34; title=&#34;HTML5 For Web Designs on the A Book Apart store&#34;&gt;HTML5 For Web Designers&lt;/a&gt; and Responsive Web Design, &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.abookapart.com/products/css3-for-web-designers&#34; title=&#34;CSS3 For Web Designers on the A Book Apart store&#34;&gt;CSS3 For Web Designers&lt;/a&gt;¬†and &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.abookapart.com/products/the-elements-of-content-strategy&#34; title=&#34;The Elements Of Content Strategy on the A Book Apart store&#34;&gt;The Elements Of Content Strategy&lt;/a&gt;, as both books I‚Äôve read so far are so informative and inspiring.¬†There‚Äôs also &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.abookapart.com/products&#34; title=&#34;A Book Apart products&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Designing for Emotion&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;Mobile First&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; to look forward to in the autumn!&lt;/p&gt;
