&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/responsive-web-design/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòResponsive Web Design‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve tried to condense &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/notes-from-ampersand-conf/&#34;&gt;my notes from Ampersand conference&lt;/a&gt; into a more useful digest. More than anything this, like my live-tweeting at past conferences, is really a selfish activity to help me absorb the ideas from Ampersand better by reflecting on the themes of the day.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And of course in the spirit of the web and all things good, I may as well share this digest so anyone who wasn‚Äôt there might get a taste of the event (albeit through my probably-twisted interpretation and slightly dodgy writing!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;using-typography&#34;&gt;Using typography&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;typography-is-about-context-context-is-about-content&#34;&gt;Typography is about context, context is about content&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The web ‚Äòindustry‚Äô is starting to focus more on content strategy, and that the whole reason our sites are there is generally to showcase content, and this was reflected in the &lt;em&gt;importance of content&lt;/em&gt; being continually brought up throughout the day.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Vincent Connare was the first speaker of the conference. As the creator of Comic Sans, Vincent was the perfect person to explain the significance of fonts being created for a purpose, for a specific context.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Comic Sans was created for Microsoft Home software, when computers were starting to become used in the home. Its fun, casual, comic-book style was based on comics like Watchmen and Batman Returns and was successfully used in speech bubbles and children‚Äôs software. It‚Äôs the prolific abuse of Comic Sans in inappropriate signage, documents, and many other places that has made it so well-known and unpopular (&lt;em&gt;or inappropriately popular!&lt;/em&gt;) As Jason Santa Maria said when talking about choosing an appropriate typeface:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;No type is born evil, it‚Äôs the context that dictates if it works.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;


    &lt;a
      href=&#39;http://www.flickr.com/photos/xxv/5446317470/&#39;
    &gt;

    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;500&#39; height=&#39;375&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/notes-from-ampersand-conference-my-digest/comicsans_hucf0f47f727eea265d72e1ea74e3cd229_142944_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/notes-from-ampersand-conference-my-digest/comicsans_hucf0f47f727eea265d72e1ea74e3cd229_142944_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/notes-from-ampersand-conference-my-digest/comicsans.jpg 500w&#39;
      src=&#39;comicsans.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Comic Sans on an Antiques shop sign&#39;
    /&gt;
      &lt;/a&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Jon Tan and Jonathan Hoefler both spoke about Bell Centennial, a font designed by Matthew Carter for phone books. The considerations in creating this font included environmental awareness, such as how the font is used and where it‚Äôs used. Matthew Carter made Bell Centennial easy to skim-read at 6pt and used ink traps for where the ink was likely to bleed on the texture of the phone book paper making the small text even harder to read.&lt;/p&gt;

