&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/future-of-web-design-2011-the-review/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòFuture Of Web Design 2011 ‚Äì; The Review‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;ive-been-at-future-of-web-design&#34;&gt;I‚Äôve been at Future Of Web Design&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The last two days were long, but fantastic, experiences at &lt;a href=&#34;http://futureofwebdesign.com&#34;&gt;Future Of Web Design&lt;/a&gt;. The talks were high quality, loads of cool people were there and I learnt a lot.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Problem is, (&lt;em&gt;from some people‚Äôs point of view&lt;/em&gt;) I tweeted a lot. I‚Äôm not going to stop, but I thought I should explain why live tweeting isn‚Äôt just &lt;strong&gt;‚Äútrying to make yourself look clever by tweeting everything you hear.‚Äù&lt;/strong&gt; (Got that from a hilariously passive aggressive tweet that wasn‚Äôt directed at me.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;taking-conference-notes&#34;&gt;Taking conference notes&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First off, there‚Äôs the selfish factor. I‚Äôm a serial note-taker. Some people learn by doing, some people learn by watching, I‚Äôm one of those people who mostly learns by writing it down. No idea why, it just goes in and gets stuck that way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;but-why-on-twitter&#34;&gt;But why on Twitter?&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I used to write pages of notes, but I‚Äôd rarely read them again, and &lt;strong&gt;nobody else could make use of them&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not everybody can afford to go to conferences. As a freelancer, I certainly can‚Äôt afford to go to many (&lt;em&gt;and I couldn‚Äôt have gone to FOWD without the awesome kindness of &lt;a href=&#34;http://cribble.net&#34;&gt;Scott Coello&lt;/a&gt; giving me his spare ticket.&lt;/em&gt;.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since I started the occasional live tweet passing comment on points in talks around two years ago, I started getting a few people saying they liked keeping up with the main themes of the conference despite not being there, and asking if I was going to live tweet the next events. I love the idea of helping people out like this, it‚Äôs not cool missing out on fantastic ideas and knowledge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;trust-me-i-am-paying-attention&#34;&gt;Trust me, I &lt;em&gt;am&lt;/em&gt; paying attention&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The bizarrest tweets I‚Äôve seen are those saying live-tweeters can‚Äôt be paying attention. How?! You‚Äôve got to pay attention to be able to tweet. Today I managed to live-tweet a talk and be the most active member of the crowd in talking to the speaker at the same time‚Ä¶I‚Äôm spend my life constantly multitasking with technology, why would a conference be any different?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;im-not-trying-to-look-clever-or-cool-or-show-off&#34;&gt;I‚Äôm not trying to look clever, or cool, or show off&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Anybody that‚Äôs knows me well knows I don‚Äôt really care about being clever, coolness isn‚Äôt really my thing and I care more about people thinking I‚Äôm a nice person than anything else.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I don‚Äôt really think live-tweeting makes me &lt;em&gt;look&lt;/em&gt; anything. Maybe noisy‚Ä¶yeah, noisy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;see-i-wouldnt-just-do-it-if-it-was-annoying-everybody&#34;&gt;See, I wouldn‚Äôt just do it if it was annoying everybody&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I can totally accept that some people don‚Äôt like tweets from conferences. To be honest, if most of my followers complained then I probably wouldn‚Äôt do it (reluctant as I am to be a slave to Twitter followers, ‚Äôcause that‚Äôs what the unfollow button is there for, right?) but I get &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/chezy/status/70467979703365633&#34;&gt;so&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/AdamWintle/status/70466722662068224&#34;&gt;many&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/GeorgeGliddon/status/70479121116966914&#34;&gt;more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/hbuchel/status/70824141082730497&#34;&gt;saying&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/suzicatherine/status/70813684078878721&#34;&gt;they&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/technokitten/status/70799014534184960&#34;&gt;find&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/chergaoui/status/70785165907070976&#34;&gt;it&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/kieranajp/status/70495588948512768&#34;&gt;handy&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm not keen on making followers grumpy but I‚Äôd much rather make some followers happy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;i-try-not-to-tweet-everything&#34;&gt;I try not to tweet everything&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm only using a phone and I don‚Äôt have lightning fingers so I couldn‚Äôt possibly tweet everything that comes out of a speaker‚Äôs mouth. I try to pick the most interesting, vital to the theme of the talk, and (most importantly) points I understand. I‚Äôll almost always put my own angle on it, as it‚Äôs how I interpret it, and to fit it into 140 characters!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;i-try-as-hard-as-possible-to-keep-the-tweets-in-context&#34;&gt;I try as hard as possible to keep the tweets in context&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It can be hard keeping in context. I‚Äôm in that environment, fully immersed, it can be tricky to distance yourself. I haven‚Äôt really had any complaints about them being confusing, but I guess people are more likely to ignore the tweets than complain that they‚Äôre nonsense.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;its-really-just-a-conference-in-bitesize&#34;&gt;It‚Äôs really just a conference in bitesize&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I find it really useful when I‚Äôm writing up conference blog posts to go back through these chunks to remind what the talks were all about. At New Adventures, and now for FOWD, I check out &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/ubelly&#34;&gt;ubelly‚Äôs tweets&lt;/a&gt; as well. Between us, I reckon we‚Äôve got the live-tweeting covered!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;but-what-if-you-hate-the-live-tweets-but-you-like-me-the-rest-of-the-time&#34;&gt;But what if you hate the live tweets but you like me the rest of the time?&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Get a decent desktop/iPhone Twitter app, such as &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.echofon.com/&#34;&gt;Echofon&lt;/a&gt;, and use the mute user or mute hashtag feature. It‚Äôs a cool temporary way to hide me, conference tweets, and any other occasionally irritating tweeters, without going through the hassle/potentially embarrassing unfollow/refollow process.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And if all else fails‚Ä¶just unfollow me!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I don‚Äôt use Twitter directly to please other people. If you‚Äôre not keen on me then chances are we won‚Äôt get along! Whilst I might be sensitive if a real friend unfollows, I understand that my particular brand of babbling nonsense isn‚Äôt for everybody.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And to be honest, not using any unfollow trackers or paying too much attention to follower figures, I‚Äôll probably never know‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
