&lt;p&gt;As a result, I have 3 conference tickets worth ¬£233.83 to give away to lovely people who want to learn more about mobile (covering topics such as innovation, usability, development, apps and mobile web.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My 3 tickets are for the first day, the conference part of The Big M, which is on &lt;strong&gt;21st March 2011&lt;/strong&gt; at Komedia in &lt;strong&gt;Bath&lt;/strong&gt; (UK.) I‚Äôd love some friendly people to come along and keep me company (that‚Äôs not an obligation!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;what-do-i-have-to-do-to-get-a-ticket&#34;&gt;What do I have to do to get a ticket?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, all you have to do to win a ticket is tweet something with the hashtag **#sendmetothebigm **or just leave me a comment below &lt;strong&gt;before 12noon tomorrow&lt;/strong&gt; (3rd March.) I‚Äôll pick three people at random after that and let you know via this blog page and via Twitter.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;what-if-i-dont-get-one&#34;&gt;What if I don‚Äôt get one?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;theres-still-some-tickets-left-on-the-big-m-websitehttpthebigmmobiregister-tickets-for-the-big-m-with-tickets-as-little-as-199-vat-for-a-conference-day-pass-and-student-conferences-passes-at-just-50-vat-youd-be-mad-to-miss-out-on-a-fun-new-event-in-beautiful-bath&#34;&gt;There‚Äôs still some tickets left on &lt;a href=&#34;http://thebigm.mobi/#register&#34; title=&#34;Tickets for The Big M&#34;&gt;The Big M website&lt;/a&gt;. With tickets as little as ¬£199 +vat for a conference day pass and student conferences passes at just ¬£50 +vat, you‚Äôd be mad to miss out on a fun new event in beautiful Bath.&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The winners, &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/laurakalbag/status/43297547447582721&#34;&gt;as announced on Twitter&lt;/a&gt; were¬†&lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/NicPresley&#34;&gt;@NicPresley&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/chrsgrrtt&#34;&gt;@chrsgrrtt&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/richquick&#34;&gt;@richquick&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/who-wants-a-ticket-for-the-big-m/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòWho wants a ticket for The Big M?‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;ive-changed-my-mind-about-this-subject&#34;&gt;I‚Äôve changed my mind about this subject!&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;to-read-about-why-and-how-i-dont-believe-this-anymore-please-read-women-and-conferenceswomen-and-conferences-women-and-conferences&#34;&gt;To read about why and how I don‚Äôt believe this anymore, &lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/women-and-conferences/&#34; title=&#34;Women and conferences&#34;&gt;please read Women and conferences&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;businesstechconferences&#34;&gt;Business‚Ä¶Tech‚Ä¶Conferences‚Ä¶&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Every time&lt;/strong&gt; I hear these dreaded phrases, ‚Äú&lt;em&gt;Women in business&lt;/em&gt;‚Äù, ‚Äú&lt;em&gt;Women in tech&lt;/em&gt;‚Äù, ‚Äú&lt;em&gt;Women at conferences&lt;/em&gt;‚Äù I just groan. It‚Äôs really boring.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Examples. ‚Äú&lt;em&gt;There‚Äôs only x% of women at this conference&lt;/em&gt;‚Äù or ‚Äú&lt;em&gt;There‚Äôs no female speakers at this conference&lt;/em&gt;.‚Äù Not just as observations (there‚Äôs nothing wrong in stating the obvious,) but saying it‚Äôs a negative point. I couldn‚Äôt care less how many other girls there are at a conference.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Asides from it being a complete bonus when there‚Äôs no queue for the Ladies, I‚Äôd rather a conference was full of eager people who bought their tickets because they were interested and wanted to engage with other attendees. Would you rather there were 100% enthusiastic, participatory attendees or a conference where there was 50/50 male/female attendees where 30% were just there to make up the numbers and weren‚Äôt bothered about being there?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As for speakers, maybe there are more male leaders (not exclusively, there are some brilliant female speakers) in the industry. The quality of a conference shouldn‚Äôt be compromised just in order to get some female speakers. Get the best speakers you can, and just don‚Äôt discriminate against having great women when they do emerge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Don‚Äôt get me wrong, I do understand people who are working for female equality. I appreciate it. I‚Äôm not really a feminist, as nowadays feminism seems to mean that men can‚Äôt say or do anything and women can act like &lt;a href=&#34;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misandry&#34; title=&#34;Misandry on Wikipedia&#34;&gt;female-equivalent of chauvinists&lt;/a&gt; as they like (See &lt;a href=&#34;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loose_Women&#34; title=&#34;Loose Women on Wikipedia&#34;&gt;Loose Women&lt;/a&gt; and other embarrassing examples.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I find being singled out as female isn‚Äôt the same as being equal. Reverse discrimination isn‚Äôt as positive as it often seems. Gender is completely irrelevant in the tech industry, certainly at conferences and definitely in business. We‚Äôre not talking about manual labour or track running here, where women and men are clearly different. Why should women be remarkable just for existing in these industries?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As a designer, I don‚Äôt think my design work reflects my gender. Certainly cultural and environmental factors must impact on my work, but design work is about context. Design work reflects the context of the project and the context of the client. I don‚Äôt like pink because I‚Äôm female but I might use pink on a site if I think it‚Äôs appropriate. I don‚Äôt think you could tell I‚Äôm a girl just by looking at my work (though correct me if I‚Äôm wrong, because if you &lt;em&gt;can&lt;/em&gt; then I‚Äôm doing something wrong!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There‚Äôs issues with most industries being male or female-dominated. That‚Äôs not going to change overnight. But in the same way, I really can‚Äôt say that anything in business, tech or conferences have ever put me off being a part of it. There are so many factors affecting genders in work, be it education, culture, or actual discrimination. Let‚Äôs just get rid of the discrimination part, and when it‚Äôs not a problem, let‚Äôs not make it an issue.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And finally, let me be completely honest. If anybody talks about me as being a ‚Äúwoman in business‚Äù, a ‚Äúwoman in tech‚Äù or a ‚Äúwoman at a conference‚Äù, not only is it weird being referred to as a &lt;strong&gt;woman&lt;/strong&gt; (I‚Äôm not that old!) but I also find it pretty fucking patronising.&lt;/p&gt;
