&lt;h2 id=&#34;my-history-with-transcending-css&#34;&gt;My history with Transcending CSS&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In 2006/early 2007 I read this amazing book. I was half way through my first year studying Digital Design, and I‚Äôd only been experimenting with standards-based web design for about six months after reading &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/1430219203?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;tag=laurkalb-21&amp;amp;linkCode=as2&amp;amp;camp=1634&amp;amp;creative=19450&amp;amp;creativeASIN=1430219203&#34;&gt;Web Standards Solutions&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I was already well on my way to being a standards fiend, but &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/redirect.html?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.co.uk%2Fs%3Fie%3DUTF8%26x%3D0%26ref_%3Dnb_sb_ss_i_3_16%26y%3D0%26field-keywords%3Dtranscending%2520css%26url%3Dsearch-alias%253Dstripbooks%26sprefix%3Dtranscending%2520css&amp;amp;tag=laurkalb-21&amp;amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;amp;camp=1634&amp;amp;creative=19450&#34;&gt;Transcending CSS&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.stuffandnonsense.co.uk/&#34; title=&#34;Stuff And Nonsense&#34;&gt;Andy Clarke&lt;/a&gt; &lt;strong&gt;did&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;em&gt;literally&lt;/em&gt;, transcend the standards and made me utterly mad about pushing the boundaries of CSS.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Transcending CSS covered properties I‚Äôd never heard of before, like z-index, and Andy Clarke wrote it with such complete conviction that you couldn‚Äôt argue with his points for progressive enhancement. I read it twice over and kept it on my desk for about two years. My only issue was that there wasn‚Äôt any index, so I wrote my own contents for the frequently-referenced pages in the front of the book in pencil.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;anticipating-hardboiled-web-design&#34;&gt;Anticipating Hardboiled Web Design&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the early days of Transcending CSS, I wasn‚Äôt on Twitter and I didn‚Äôt much follow the ‚Äòindustry‚Äô around web design. I wasn‚Äôt really sure who Andy Clarke was, I just knew that he wrote this book I really liked.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Three years later and I‚Äôm a full time freelance designer, always on Twitter, and always trying to keep up with the latest and greatest in the most practical way possible. When Hardboiled Web Design was announced by Five Simple Steps, I‚Äôll admit I was pretty excited. I loved &lt;a href=&#34;http://fivesimplesteps.com/books/practical-guide-designing-for-the-web&#34;&gt;A Practical Guide to Designing For The Web&lt;/a&gt; (also by &lt;a href=&#34;http://fivesimplesteps.com/&#34;&gt;Five Simple Steps&lt;/a&gt;) which only made me keener.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I followed all of &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/malarkey&#34; title=&#34;Andy Clarke on Twitter&#34;&gt;Andy‚Äôs tweets&lt;/a&gt; about &lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#!/search/%23hardboiledwebdesign&#34; title=&#34;Twitter search for #hardboiledwebdesign&#34;&gt;#hardboiledwebdesign&lt;/a&gt; so I knew what to expect from the book. As I‚Äôm now following the goings-on of HTML5 and CSS3 a lot closer, I knew it probably wouldn‚Äôt have the same appeal as my &lt;em&gt;wow-this-is-what-the-web-can-really-do&lt;/em&gt; awe of Transcending CSS, but it still didn‚Äôt disappoint.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;hardboiled-web-design&#34;&gt;Hardboiled Web Design&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The book is predictably well-written. It‚Äôs not too formal, not overly-instructional and very friendly. That‚Äôs already an improvement on the majority of books about web development. Sometimes the tone is a bit &lt;em&gt;scary-in-a-good-way&lt;/em&gt;, you can really tell how much Andy cares about pushing the web forward.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The book is themed around detective stories. I found the detective novel references a bit much at times, but that‚Äôs because I‚Äôve never read any (not that I wouldn‚Äôt, I just haven‚Äôt!) It started to feel a bit like an in-joke I wasn‚Äôt a part of, but did make for lovely illustrations and content examples.&lt;/p&gt;

