&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/good-old-designer-snobbery-is-alive-and-kicking/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòGood old designer snobbery is alive and kicking‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A couple of weeks ago I created a quickie logo for Andy Warburton‚Äôs mobile stock photography service Stockyoo. Andy was really keen on the idea of using &lt;a href=&#34;http://forrst.com&#34;&gt;Forrst&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;http://dribbble.com&#34;&gt;Dribbble&lt;/a&gt; for posting the progress of the project to get the opinions of potential users of a stock photography service and do some early promo for Stockyoo itself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;dribbble-and-forrst&#34;&gt;Dribbble and Forrst&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dribbble and Forrst are part of a new wave of sites aimed at (mostly web) designers and developers. Dribbble allows its users to post 300 x 400px teaser snapshots of their work. Forrst has wider options of posting any image, URL, piece of code or question. Both encourage feedback from other users in the form of comments. Dribbble also encourages ‚Äòrebounds‚Äô where users can rework an existing snapshot and repost it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve been a member &lt;a href=&#34;http://dribbble.com/players/laurakalbag&#34; title=&#34;Laura Kalbag on Dribbble&#34;&gt;on Dribbble&lt;/a&gt; since January and &lt;a href=&#34;http://forrst.com/people/laurakalbag/posts&#34; title=&#34;Laura Kalbag on Forrst&#34;&gt;on Forrst&lt;/a&gt; since the beginning of August, and I was happy to post my work in progress. I‚Äôm not &lt;em&gt;too much&lt;/em&gt; of an ego to have my work critiqued, and I thought it‚Äôd be a fun experiment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-process&#34;&gt;The Process&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I didn‚Äôt post every tiny iteration of the Stockyoo logo online as I thought it‚Äôd drive people mad. I had twelve images in total (&lt;a href=&#34;http://forrst.com/people/laurakalbag/posts&#34; title=&#34;All my Stockyoo posts on Forrst&#34;&gt;all posted to Forrst&lt;/a&gt;) which covered four or five major iterations of the design. As soon as I felt ready to send something to Andy for feedback, that was when I felt ready to post the images online.&lt;/p&gt;

