&lt;h2 id=&#34;benefits-of-using-dribbble-and-forrst-for-feedback&#34;&gt;Benefits of using Dribbble and Forrst for feedback&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are a lot of benefits for using Dribbble and Forrst for feedback if you‚Äôre not overly sensitive to criticism.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;affirmation-for-a-client&#34;&gt;Affirmation for a client&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If a client is unsure of their feelings, or needs an outside opinion, they can see the reactions of others and use those reactions to help affirm their own beliefs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If other designers (especially if they‚Äôre part of the target audience) have positive feelings towards your work then it can help convince a client that you‚Äôre heading in the right direction, even if the client feels otherwise.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;thoughtful-opinions-and-inspiration&#34;&gt;Thoughtful opinions and inspiration&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you‚Äôre struggling with some design (or code on Forrst) other users might have that valuable insight or piece of inspiration to help you on your way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;early-promotion&#34;&gt;Early promotion&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is likely to be especially effective where the users of Dribbble or Forrst are your target audience. Getting an idea of how these users feel towards your brand is very valuable. You‚Äôll make them feel more important for asking them how they think, and giving them a part to play in the creation of the brand is likely to create a feeling of ownership and loyalty.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-negative-side&#34;&gt;The negative side&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;time&#34;&gt;Time&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It takes a reasonable amount of time to post to Dribbble and Forrst. Making sure the screenshot shows enough, uploading everything and adding tags can take half an hour or so, especially when you‚Äôre doing a few images at a time. This isn‚Äôt a reflection on either site‚Äôs experience, they‚Äôre both very easy to use, but if you‚Äôre trying to add a useful description to your post it can take a pretty long time which brings me to‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;its-hard-to-provide-context&#34;&gt;It‚Äôs hard to provide context&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The users viewing, liking and commenting on your images haven‚Äôt seen the brief, the communication between you and the client or tried other ideas out already. A small description isn‚Äôt really enough to give much context so a lot of the opinions you‚Äôll get on your work is little more than ‚Äúthat‚Äôs pretty‚Äù or ‚Äúthat‚Äôs ugly‚Äù.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;subjective-and-unhelpful-opinions&#34;&gt;Subjective and unhelpful opinions&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Somebody saying ‚Äúthat‚Äôs great‚Äù is all very lovely and ego-soothing, but doesn‚Äôt have much depth. An overall positive response is definitely better than negative, but without reasons and justifications in comments, it‚Äôs not going to help you better your work.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-conclusion&#34;&gt;The conclusion&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I think the benefits and negatives above apply to the overall usage of Dribbble and Forrst. It‚Äôs great for popularity contests and making yourself feel big and clever, but helpful feedback is often rare (especially if you don‚Äôt ask for it!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôd like to try using Dribbble and Forrst for feedback on a longer-term project. I can imagine they‚Äôre potentially useful for the in-house designers of web apps, creating a buzz around teaser shots and getting feedback on visual elements, especially if they‚Äôre used regularly.&lt;/p&gt;
