&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/using-dribbble-and-forrst-for-feedback-on-a-client-project/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòUsing Dribbble and Forrst for feedback on a client project‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was a bit skeptical about dConstruct at first. The idea of a conference based on ‚Äòcreativity and ideas‚Äô made me worry it might be a bit pretentious but I was convinced by a lot of friends on Twitter that it‚Äôd be worthwhile, and they were so right.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I went with a notebook and an open mind. I didn‚Äôt want to go all reverse-snob on the pretentious (something I‚Äôm generally pretty guilty of being) and be ignorant of learning when I‚Äôd paid ¬£¬£s for the pleasure.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And I ended up writing reams. Well, seven sides of a scruffy notebook, so here are the best bits I remember from each talk for the benefit of my friends who couldn‚Äôt be there.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;summaries&#34;&gt;Summaries&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve tried to summarise the main ideas from the talks. If I totally missed the point or didn‚Äôt do it justice, I‚Äôm really sorry!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;marty-neumeier--the-designful-company&#34;&gt;Marty Neumeier ‚Äî The Designful Company&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Branding is about how the consumer &lt;em&gt;feels&lt;/em&gt; about your product. To differentiate your brand from others, you must be good &lt;strong&gt;and&lt;/strong&gt; different.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;brendan-dawes--boil-simmer-reduce&#34;&gt;Brendan Dawes ‚Äî Boil, Simmer, Reduce&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Collect as much inspiration and information as possible, consider it all and the reduce it down until there‚Äôs nothing left to take away.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;david-mccandless--information-is-beautiful&#34;&gt;David McCandless ‚Äî Information Is Beautiful&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Infographics can be used to help us understand and relate to the huge amount of information and data we‚Äôre drowning in.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;samantha-warren--the-power-and-beauty-of-typography&#34;&gt;Samantha Warren ‚Äî The Power and Beauty of Typography&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Letters can say more than the words they spell. Picking fonts for a project is like picking shoes for an outfit, you must pick the most contextually appropriate font.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;john-gruber--the-auteur-theory-of-design&#34;&gt;John Gruber ‚Äî The Auteur Theory Of Design&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Much like in film production, collaborative web projects can benefit from an auteur who acts as an arbiter of taste and strives for high quality.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;hannah-donovan--jam-session-what-improvisation-can-teach-us-about-design&#34;&gt;Hannah Donovan ‚Äî Jam Session: What Improvisation Can Teach Us About Design&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We can learn about improvisation in design from improvisation in music. Making sure tools don‚Äôt get in the way, we have a structure to follow and roles to keep, to help us free our self-expression.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;james-bridle--the-value-of-ruins&#34;&gt;James Bridle ‚Äî The Value Of Ruins&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We need to make sure information is being kept, given history, value and versions to help us understand its context, the world and protect the information from cultural destruction.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;tom-coates--everything-the-network-touches&#34;&gt;Tom Coates ‚Äî Everything The Network Touches&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The future is in the connectivity of data, up to huge scales such a cities&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;merlin-mann--kerning-orgasms-amp-those-goddamned-japanese-toothpicks&#34;&gt;Merlin Mann ‚Äî Kerning, Orgasms &amp;amp; Those Goddamned Japanese Toothpicks&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Nerd are cool because they really care about something. It‚Äôs great to be a nerd because you suck up huge quantities of information. It‚Äôs important to ensure you keep the information up-to-date and relevant.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;various-points-and-ideas&#34;&gt;Various points and ideas&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve tried to capture some of the ideas from my notes in this mind map thing, in addition/support to the summaries. If you can read my writing, you might find it interesting. I just did it to help cement the ideas in my head as I‚Äôm one of those people who has to write something down a million times to get it to stick.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;img src=&#34;finished-mindmap.gif&#34; alt=&#34;dConstruct 2010 ideas mindmap&#34;&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;overall-conference-thoughts&#34;&gt;Overall conference thoughts&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The more people I know, the better conferences always are. It can be pretty hard to get chatting to somebody you don‚Äôt know in a room full of people who are stereotypically shy (especially when you‚Äôre in a minority of girls and so stick out like a sore thumb!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I loved Brighton as a destination (pretty easy travel for me) and the venue was very smart. It was a bit tricky to write notes in the darker parts of the theatre but wouldn‚Äôt be so hard on back-lit devices (I opted for paper as I‚Äôm still really slow on iPad.) It would have been great to charge my iPhone/iPad during the talks as most of my break times were spent out of the venue trying to find non-coffee/tea refreshments.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What I noticed in particular was that there weren‚Äôt any questions at the end of the talks. In a way this was good because it prevented the awkward silence that is often heralded with ‚ÄòAny questions?‚Äô at other conferences. However, it did give you the feeling of one-way communication. Much more like being at a lecture than being in a lesson.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It was good to see speakers I hadn‚Äôt seen before too. I think I‚Äôd already seen a variation of Brendan Dawes‚Äô talk at Future Of Web Design, but otherwise the talks and speakers were totally new to me. This was refreshing over some of the conference veterans, because how much do you practice what you preach when you spend your whole time touring a talk?!&lt;/p&gt;
