&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/dconstruct-2010/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòdConstruct 2010‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There‚Äôs something that‚Äôs been niggling at me for ages. The way people act as if they‚Äôre a multi-person company when they‚Äôre really just one individual. This whole ‚Äòwe‚Äô syndrome.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We have a great new client now working with us at Just Little Old Me Ltd.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sometimes it makes me giggle when I know somebody is an individual ‚Äòme‚Äô and they‚Äôre saying ‚Äòwe‚Äô as if they‚Äôre some kind of medieval queen. I just can‚Äôt help feeling it‚Äôs a little bit deceptive to act in this way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;why-bother&#34;&gt;Why bother?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I can see there‚Äôs a couple of reasons why people feel the need to pretend to be bigger than they really are:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It makes them look big and official to others, making them look more trustworthy. &lt;em&gt;That company won‚Äôt run away with my money, but that single cowboy there might do&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It seems to give them some kind of prestige over that teenage kid working in his bedroom. &lt;em&gt;Oh, it‚Äôs not just a student, they‚Äôre a proper company&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;but-really-why-do-we-do-this&#34;&gt;But really, why do we do this?&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The web is still young, and it‚Äôs incredibly difficult to tell the hardworking souls from the shady characters. If most of your communication is web-based, without meeting face-to-face or even speaking on the phone, it‚Äôs hard for a client to pick up on those gut instincts and little signs that tells you somebody can‚Äôt be trusted.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We‚Äôve come to inherently trust bigger companies. People will eat in a chain restaurant because they know what to expect. Companies made up of multiple people appear to be more stable because there‚Äôs more people to get the work done.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I can understand why it looks good to be big company.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;its-just-being-deceptive&#34;&gt;It‚Äôs just being deceptive&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What I really don‚Äôt understand about people who create this fa√ßade of a multiple person company is that they‚Äôre losing all the benefits of appearing to be trustworthy and stable. If you‚Äôre lying (however well-intended that lie is,) you‚Äôre no-longer credible. I have an immediate distrust of anybody who claims who says ‚Äòwe‚Äô when they‚Äôre really just a ‚Äòme‚Äô as I wonder what other truths they‚Äôre bending.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Saying ‚Äòwe‚Äô and talking as a company and not an individual also makes you seem detached. Is your company persona all that different from your individual persona? If it is, then why? Why do you have to pretend to be a different person to do business?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;its-really-not-all-that-bad-being-a-me&#34;&gt;It‚Äôs really not all that bad being a ‚Äòme‚Äô&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm Laura Kalbag, I‚Äôm a sole trader and my company is called ‚ÄòLaura Kalbag‚Äô. What you see really is what you get. Sometimes I sense a lack of trust in me because I‚Äôm not an agency or a big company. You know what, I don‚Äôt care. I‚Äôd rather not work with somebody who suspects I might not be reliable. If we‚Äôre starting out with some big fat negative preconceptions, it‚Äôs going to be harder to get positive feelings from that person.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As an individual, people can be assured that:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I‚Äôm the one doing all the work. They will talk to me and I will execute the designs, development etc all based on our direct conversation. There‚Äôs less room for misinterpretation if there‚Äôs only one link in the chain.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I‚Äôm as vulnerable as them. Weakness isn‚Äôt always negative. I‚Äôve got to directly make money to have food and shelter, so have my clients. It‚Äôs much more personal when you‚Äôre not throwing somebody else‚Äôs money around.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I don‚Äôt have to check that what I‚Äôm saying is the right thing on behalf of my company and/or employer. Ditch all the legalese, I‚Äôm talking to you man-to-man (or girl-to-man or girl-to-girl, you see what I mean!)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;i-feel-like-im-good-enough&#34;&gt;I feel like I‚Äôm good enough&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There‚Äôs upsides and downsides to hiring a freelancer or an agency but the important thing is that I‚Äôm happy with what I am. If you‚Äôve got no confidence in yourself as an individual freelancer, then go find yourself some like-minds and form an agency!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs not arrogance to say I feel like I‚Äôm good enough to speak as myself. I‚Äôve got as many insecurities as the next person but I enjoy being a human, friendly face in a sea of (often) faceless companies.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So next time you‚Äôre thinking of saying ‚Äòwe‚Äô when you just mean ‚Äòme‚Äô, think about how much that little word means. I think it‚Äôd be better if everybody was a little bit more honest.&lt;/p&gt;
