	&lt;div class=&#34;comment-entry&#34;&gt;
		I guess and you&amp;#039;re right ‚Äì; from your statement, you&amp;#039;re a &amp;#039;me&amp;#039;.
&lt;p&gt;IÔøΩm talking more about single-owner companies with no full-time employees, but they have other companies or self-employed people that they consistently subcontract work to.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As an example, a web designer may be asked to implement a website that requires some technical skill, some development/integration work, some copywriting, etc.  Under these circumstances, provided thereÔøΩs money for it, that designer may decide to subcontract elements out (get an engineer in for a couple of hours for the technical work, subcontract development and copyrighting work to third parties‚Ä¶).  Would it be wrong to refer to the web designerÔøΩs company as a ÔøΩmeÔøΩ in a tender?  It certainly would not be a ÔøΩmeÔøΩ who completed the work.  However, if all the work is whitelabelled (done under the web designerÔøΩs brand, all paid to the web designer then paid on as appropriate), why shouldnÔøΩt they call themselves ÔøΩweÔøΩ?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;IÔøΩm playing devilÔøΩs advocate to a degree.  It doesnÔøΩt affect where I work (weÔøΩre definitely a ÔøΩweÔøΩ) but we provide technical resources to companies who are ÔøΩmeÔøΩs, but promote themselves as ÔøΩweÔøΩs.  Do I think it ever really makes a difference when we go up against them?  Not really.  And, from the customerÔøΩs perspective, as long as theyÔøΩre getting what they asked for and are happy with the service, why should they mind?
&lt;/div&gt;
