&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/year-one/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòYear One‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don‚Äôt like to say it, but I think the Girlguides UK campaign (&lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#search?q=%23gukforrealimages&#34; title=&#34;hashtag search on Twitter&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://twitter.com/#search?q=%23gukforrealimages&#34; title=&#34;hashtag search on Twitter&#34;&gt;gukforrealimages&lt;/a&gt;) call for labelling all airbrushed images of women is unrealistic.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our¬†girls and young women are demanding action from the Prime Minister to introduce compulsory labelling to distinguish between airbrushed and natural imagesin order to ‚Äòshape a generation of self-confident girls and young women.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(Tell us the truth ‚Äì; Girls call for honesty over airbrushing.¬†&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.girlguiding.org.uk/system_pages/small_navigation/latest_news/tell_us_the_truth.aspx&#34;&gt;Girlguiding website&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôm a girl, and I‚Äôve had all the usual confidence issues growing up that are no doubt in-part created by the unhealthy portrayal of women in the media. Many girls (and boys) would certainly benefit from there being more natural body shapes being shown in advertising and the media in general. If it‚Äôs going to be aspirational, then it should give people aspirations of realistic, achievable goals.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, I‚Äôm not sure that the lines between air brushing (by which I assume they mean altering the appearance of a model) and post-production are clear enough. I think it is probably near-impossible to find a commercial image out there that hasn‚Äôt had some kind of post-production applied. It could be anything from changing the colouring and exposure all the way to placing a model into an artificial environment. In post production the artist is designing the image to suit the advertising campaign in every possible way, this will inevitably mean changes from the very raw basic image shot in a studio. If all the images used in commercial campaigns looked like our holiday snaps, they wouldn‚Äôt have the desired effect. Commercial campaigns are designed to make us want to be like the people in the photos, be it richer, slimmer or just happier.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There‚Äôs already been labelling in TV ads. All the mascara advertisements now have a ‚Äòenhanced in post production‚Äô label at some point. It‚Äôs obvious that nobody could get eyelashes a mile long with a plain old high street mascara so it‚Äôs false advertising. Does this labelling work? Do children understand what post production is? Does everybody read the small text on TV adverts? I don‚Äôt really think so. It just means nobody‚Äôs going to sue the cosmetics companies.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;How do the Girlguides propose these images should be labelled? If there‚Äôs an image where nothing has been done except the smoothing of a girl‚Äôs skin and applying some extra eye makeup, how is that distinguished by a label from an image where they‚Äôve given her somebody else‚Äôs breasts, trimmed her waist by six inches, changed the colour of her hair, the colour of her skin and lengthened her eyelashes. Does each image then have to come with a list of everything the digital artist did to perfect the photo? I‚Äôd imagine on most campaigns there‚Äôd be more label than photo!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Where then do they draw the line at what needs to be labelled? TV adverts, magazines, billboards, clothes catalogues so also clothes store websites, packaging, DVD, CD and book covers. You can see where I‚Äôm going with this‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Rather than going guns blazing into a campaign to label as many commercial images as possible ‚Äòfake‚Äô, I think it would be far more productive to try to tackle these problems at the root. Why do we aspire to be ridiculously thin? Who are the role models that make us this way? Can we change the attitudes of the influencers, the magazines and advertisers that insist on these bizarre body images being what we should aspire to?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I think it‚Äôs great that the Girlguides are drawing attention to these issues but there‚Äôs much more to them than dodgy photos and a bit of small print to fix the perceptions of young girls.&lt;/p&gt;
