&lt;h2 id=&#34;fan-girl&#34;&gt;Fan girl&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve had an iPad since the day it was released in the UK. I bought it because I‚Äôm a fan girl. I admit it. I could pretend that I wanted it to take to conferences or use for testing or when I didn‚Äôt need a laptop when I went to visit clients. In truth, I only go to one or two conferences per year, I‚Äôve not yet made a site that needed an iPad-specific site and when I go to visit clients I &lt;strong&gt;always&lt;/strong&gt; need my laptop. I was simply justifying my desire to have something shiny.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When my iPad arrived I was in love with the glossy screen, the simple gestures and the idea of all the tasks I could now complete without using my laptop. Thing is, it doesn‚Äôt run Photoshop or &lt;a href=&#34;http://panic.com/coda/&#34; title=&#34;A lovely web development tool&#34;&gt;Coda&lt;/a&gt; or any of the apps I actually &lt;em&gt;need&lt;/em&gt; for working. It may suit other people who just need a word processor, spreadsheet or presentation software, but when it comes to specialist tools the iPad isn‚Äôt the device.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;workaholic&#34;&gt;Workaholic&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Yet more and more I‚Äôm finding that the iPad is stopping me from going mad. Being a freelancer that works from home, it‚Äôs very difficult to switch off. I often have days where I sit at my desk til six, then just move my laptop to the TV and carry on working until it‚Äôs time to sleep. This is a really bad habit and just leads to all-work-and-no-play and a big fat stress-face. Many wise people talk about keeping normal office hours and being equally productive and there‚Äôs a lot of truth in that.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now I leave my laptop when I‚Äôm finished working, turn it off and engage iPad. I can‚Äôt work with the iPad, so I won‚Äôt. I can read e-mails, but if I reply from my iPad I won‚Äôt have a record of the reply on my laptop for reference (so I rarely do that.) I can visit as many websites as I like, but I won‚Äôt be writing any HTML or CSS. I can sketch and doodle ideas and even make brainstorms but I won‚Äôt be creating any graphics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The result is a total separation of work and play. The iPad fulfils all my casual browsing needs and I‚Äôm a more sociable and less stressed being.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;playtime&#34;&gt;Playtime&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There‚Äôs added bonuses to this too. There are plenty of cool apps on the iPad to keep me entertained.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;ibooks&#34;&gt;iBooks&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A couple of weeks ago I read my first full book (albeit a reasonably short 200-page one) using &lt;a href=&#34;http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/ibooks/id364709193?mt=8&#34; title=&#34;iBooks on the App Store&#34;&gt;iBooks&lt;/a&gt;. To all those saying it doesn‚Äôt beat a real book, I say stop being so old-fashioned. If you‚Äôre used to staring at a screen for 12 hours a day, your eyes won‚Äôt particularly complain. I set the settings to large-ish text, changed the colouring to sepia and turned the brightness down. My eyes were very happy.&lt;/p&gt;

