    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, if you‚Äôre like me and tap away at a few blog posts at once, dipping in to edit them every now and again, WordPress for iPad is great for a distraction-free environment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;twitterrific&#34;&gt;Twitterrific&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Many people would agree that &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.atebits.com/tweetie-mac/&#34;&gt;Tweetie&lt;/a&gt; is the most native-style mac Twitter client. I used &lt;a href=&#34;http://iconfactory.com/software/twitterrific&#34;&gt;Twitterrific for mac&lt;/a&gt; before I was a Tweetie fan and it just feels too &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.adobe.com/products/air/&#34;&gt;Adobe-Airy&lt;/a&gt;. It doesn‚Äôt feel native, it doesn‚Äôt quite look right, there‚Äôs something a bit flimsy about it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But &lt;a href=&#34;http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/twitterrific-for-twitter/id359914600?mt=8&#34;&gt;Twitterrific on iPad&lt;/a&gt; is a revelation. Landscape mode is totally where it‚Äôs at, it has the extra column/menu down the left hand side. Easy to browse, packed full of features (maybe not so many as &lt;a href=&#34;http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/twitter/id333903271?mt=8&#34;&gt;Twitter for iPhone&lt;/a&gt; or the so-ugly-I-seriously-can‚Äôt-stand-it &lt;a href=&#34;http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/tweetdeck-for-ipad/id364153769?mt=8&#34;&gt;Tweetdeck&lt;/a&gt;) but for a casual addict it feels just right.&lt;/p&gt;

