&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;font-size: 23px; color: #000000; line-height: 35px;&#34;&gt;Finding Apps&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The downside to the iPad is app discoverability. Despite Apple selling so many devices, there don‚Äôt seem to be many iPads around. People aren‚Äôt constantly talking about new iPad apps on Twitter like they do with iPhone apps. There‚Äôs very rarely that word-of-mouth way to happen across a cool app.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So you have to rely on the App Store. Unless you‚Äôre after a top 10 app, or a random Staff Pick that‚Äôs been sitting there for a month, you just have to search and hope. You can wade through pages and pages of mediocre apps in the Categories trying to find that rare gem. It‚Äôs incredibly difficult to be paired up with something you‚Äôll like, use, and will be worth the relatively high cost of often ¬£5.99+.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/appstream-for-ipad/id375288393?mt=8&#34;&gt;Appsfire‚Äôs App Stream&lt;/a&gt; is trying to solve the discoverability problem. A stream of small app icons rotate around the board. You can tap them to see more, basically all the info you get in the app store. If you like it, you can tap again to view and purchase on the App Store.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/how-the-ipad-is-saving-my-sanity/appstream_hu9a8e32fe0c7e30d88ad2daae33ee1514_403354_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/how-the-ipad-is-saving-my-sanity/appstream_hu9a8e32fe0c7e30d88ad2daae33ee1514_403354_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/how-the-ipad-is-saving-my-sanity/appstream_hu9a8e32fe0c7e30d88ad2daae33ee1514_403354_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/how-the-ipad-is-saving-my-sanity/appstream.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;appstream.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;App stream by Appsfire&#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;App stream by Appsfire is useful but not totally beautiful&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Unfortunately this really relies on you judging a book by its cover. The slickest, prettiest icons are most likely to catch your attention and you‚Äôre most likely to assume the apps with duff icons are going to have a rubbish app design. Whilst it‚Äôs pretty likely, I feel like this random stream of icons is as bad as trying to filter through App Store listings. It‚Äôs a bit faster to load, but you‚Äôre not even getting any contextual category or ranking information.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As the Apple app stores get huger, there‚Äôs going to be a much greater need for discovering the best apps for the individual. I can imagine there‚Äôs a lot more startups getting into these areas and I‚Äôd love to hear if anybody out there has any recommendations for me! I want to get even more out of my iPad time!&lt;/p&gt;
