&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/html5-for-web-designers/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòHTML5 For Web Designers‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This little post is an extension of my post on Web Fonts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Of late, some of the snobbier designers are whining that more fonts available will mean the web will get covered in horrible mis-use of fonts, unreadable body text and general ugliness.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I don‚Äôt think this is totally fair, but I‚Äôm sure some people might get confused by the variety of fonts that are around, so I thought I‚Äôd share a few things I try to keep in mind when choosing fonts:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;use-appropriate-fonts&#34;&gt;Use appropriate fonts&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Easily said, I know, but some fonts are clearly more suitable for particular designs than others. For example, you wouldn‚Äôt use a font that looks like it‚Äôs dripping blood on a corporate site, and you‚Äôd not use a handwriting-style font on a site about computer programming.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;678&#39; height=&#39;78&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.39.37_hu061d49b71e98bb8fcf1ffcaa1aa14d30_17506_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.39.37_hu061d49b71e98bb8fcf1ffcaa1aa14d30_17506_500x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 500w,/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.39.37.png 678w&#39;
      src=&#39;Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.39.37.png&#39; alt=&#39;Firey font isn&amp;#39;t really suitable for Daisy&amp;#39;s Darling Cake shop&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you‚Äôre aiming for clean and modern, go sans-serif. If you‚Äôre looking for a slightly more traditional feel, go serif.
&lt;h3 id=&#34;dont-use-more-than-two-fonts&#34;&gt;Don‚Äôt use more than two fonts&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;With all these cool fonts around, it‚Äôs easy to go over-the-top and try out loads at once. Unless you‚Äôre going for a Victorian poster style, I‚Äôd steer clear of the multi-font look.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;portrait&#39;
      width=&#39;589&#39; height=&#39;743&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/picking-fonts/Circus_Montreal_9_March_1812_hu895c727476d934e601ef285cd4b071d2_316701_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/picking-fonts/Circus_Montreal_9_March_1812_hu895c727476d934e601ef285cd4b071d2_316701_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/picking-fonts/Circus_Montreal_9_March_1812.jpg 589w&#39;
      src=&#39;Circus_Montreal_9_March_1812.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Old Victorian circus poster, lots and lots of fonts&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs difficult to find two fonts that match each other well. You want to look for as similar shapes as possible, round fonts with other circle-based fonts, condensed fonts with other tall, thin fonts.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;435&#39; height=&#39;144&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.48.50_hu5623a61520444beba71cb5522d354aef_25910_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.48.50.png 435w&#39;
      src=&#39;Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.48.50.png&#39; alt=&#39;Kaffeesatz as a header font with Droid Sans as the body font&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you‚Äôre really struggling to combine two, just use a different weight or style for the heading, like bold or all uppercase.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;440&#39; height=&#39;134&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.51.45_huccba4da97cb612a260d69f07d03b4fcc_30497_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.51.45.png 440w&#39;
      src=&#39;Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.51.45.png&#39; alt=&#39;Georgia as header and body font&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Mark Boulton covers these kinds of combinations in his fantastic book, A Practical Guide to Designing For The Web.
&lt;h3 id=&#34;keep-it-in-the-family&#34;&gt;Keep it in the family&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The easiest way to find two fonts that suit each other is to take two from the same family. These are always designed around the same shapes so you know they‚Äôll look good next to each other. This is particularly useful if you want to mix serif and sans-serif fonts. For example, the Museo family. Museo Sans, Museo Serif and Museo Slab all look great used in any combination.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;453&#39; height=&#39;278&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.55.53_hu479648e9590f18075dc106a64fdedc0d_49991_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.55.53.png 453w&#39;
      src=&#39;Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.55.53.png&#39; alt=&#39;The Museo Family&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&#34;use-simple-fonts-for-body-text&#34;&gt;Use simple fonts for body text&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Whatever you do, leave the fancy fonts for the headings. With body text (paragraph text,) you‚Äôre aiming for readability above all else. Using any kind of fancy, looping, scrawly, drippy, firey font here will make it hard to read and really distract the reader.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;458&#39; height=&#39;283&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.59.14_hu81407e81f802e885f0a5b5e12c7aa0cb_58763_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.59.14.png 458w&#39;
      src=&#39;Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-18.59.14.png&#39; alt=&#39;A paragraph in Papyrus&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&#34;use-lovely-long-font-stacks&#34;&gt;Use lovely long font stacks&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bear in mind that, whatever fancy web font method you use, there will always be a user that can‚Äôt see that font. It might be because their browser doesn‚Äôt have javascript turned on, or doesn‚Äôt support @font-face or doesn‚Äôt have the system font you specified. Solve this problem by using as many similar fonts as possible in your font stack.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For example, I want to use Museo Sans as my body font on this page. My code would look like:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;body { font-family: &amp;quot;Museo Sans&amp;quot;, &amp;quot;Perspective Sans&amp;quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; }&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Typekit will provide Museo Sans for me, so I‚Äôll put that first in my font stack.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In case the user doesn‚Äôt have javascript enabled (or uses Opera!) I‚Äôll specify an @font-face font I found on Font Squirrel, Perspective Sans.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;For the rare case that don‚Äôt support Typekit or @font-face, I‚Äôll specify the system font Helvetica.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Just in case a user doesn‚Äôt even have Helvetica, I‚Äôll also specify the wildly popular system font, Arial.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;And for the user who for some reason has only weird fonts I‚Äôve never heard of on their computer, I‚Äôll specify sans-serif, so at least I know that they‚Äôre not being delivered a serif font when I really fancied sans.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not much effort, maximum kindness to the user.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;keep-the-poor-windows-users-in-mind&#34;&gt;Keep the poor Windows users in mind&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Whichever fonts you choose, you want to make sure it looks good in as many browsers as possible. For us lucky mac users, the fonts tend to normally look smooth and light and lovely. Unfortunately many Windows users aren‚Äôt so lucky. Craggy, pixelly and oddly squashed-looking fonts are very common.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;figure&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;232&#39; height=&#39;104&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/picking-fonts/Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-19.14.52.jpg 232w&#39;
      src=&#39;Screen-shot-2010-07-05-at-19.14.52.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;Typodermic&amp;#39;s Bouffant font in Mac&amp;#39;s Safari (top) and Windows&amp;#39; Internet Explorer 6 (bottom) &#39;
    /&gt;

    &lt;figcaption&gt;


      &lt;p&gt;Typodermic‚Äôs Bouffant font in Mac‚Äôs Safari (top) and Windows‚Äô Internet Explorer 6 (bottom)&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Many Windows people aren‚Äôt as fussy as me, or just don‚Äôt notice, but it‚Äôs really worth checking that what the Windows‚Äô users see is actually &lt;em&gt;legible&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This quick little guide is just the beginning of all the things I try to consider when I‚Äôm choosing fonts to use on the web. A lot of it feels automatic, but when I really think about it, there‚Äôs all sorts of rules and theory I‚Äôm trying to apply to my choices. And that‚Äôs still not saying I always get it right. To a degree, it is still a subjective choice.&lt;/p&gt;
