Overall, my preferred web font solution is definitely Typekit. The exciting thing is that new solutions keep popping up all time, so I‚Äôm sure the best is yet to come. For now, I have to do a complicated mix of Typekit, @font-face and standard system fonts to cover all bases so I‚Äôm really looking forward to the day we have a robust solution that does it all for me!
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/web-fonts/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòWeb Fonts‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve always been a kind-of arty person. I took Art at school, did an Art Foundation and a Graphics degree. I totally loved art when I was small, but as I‚Äôve got older, and more technology and web-obsessed, a lot of the old media went a bit out of the window.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Though I was still loving wireframing and taking notes by hand, I just threw all the paints out in frustration at how slow and difficult they were.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôd seen the iPad apps available before launch, and Autodesk‚Äôs SketchBook Pro caught my eye. The idea of drawing on-screen is pretty appealing (I never really got the hang of the chunkiness of the Wacom tablet) and SketchBook Pro is better than I expected.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is my most recent drawing:&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_huc10f1a22659aca1d23273dfa2c15ee51_118158_300x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 300w,/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_huc10f1a22659aca1d23273dfa2c15ee51_118158_500x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 500w,/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_huc10f1a22659aca1d23273dfa2c15ee51_118158_800x0_resize_q80_mitchellnetravali.jpg 800w,/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo.jpg 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;photo.jpg&#39; alt=&#39;drawing of a fish using SketchBook Pro&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was sitting at the fishing lake at Longleat, sketching from a photo in Matt‚Äôs fishing magazine whilst he fishes. (And using the WordPress app for writing this, but that‚Äôs a story for another time.) Asides from the sunlight making it a bit tricky to see anything other than my greasy fingerprints, it felt incredibly natural painting with my finger. Some clever person has probably come up with a way of using a stylus but I think that might spoil some of the charm. Finger painting is a bit thick, blobby and impressionist. I‚Äôm actually surprised by how much this looks like if I‚Äôd painted it in acrylics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;SketchBook Pro uses gestures as naturally as any native iPad app. You use 3-finger tap to open the tools, 2-finger pinch and drag for resizing and moving the canvas on the screen (so you can zoom for the fiddly bits) and a 3-finger left-to-right drag to undo your last marks (and right-to-left for redo.) I‚Äôm usually a bit rubbish at remembering all these kind of gestures but they just &lt;em&gt;feel so right&lt;/em&gt; that it‚Äôs easy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The capabilities of the tools are just amazing for an iPad app.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;the-brushes-palette&#34;&gt;The Brushes palette&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_4_hu56618f63458f3e52347b58ccd54a7ee6_294138_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_4_hu56618f63458f3e52347b58ccd54a7ee6_294138_500x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 500w,/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_4_hu56618f63458f3e52347b58ccd54a7ee6_294138_800x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 800w,/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_4.png 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;photo_4.png&#39; alt=&#39;the brushes palette in SketchBook Pro&#39;
    /&gt;
The amount of elements you can combine to create your own style and perfect the texture and colour you want are just incredible. I‚Äôve not even tried everything yet, but some of my favourite elements are:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Radius‚Äîfor going from the rough fat splodges to the tiniest little pixels, this gives you very fine-tuned control though it can be tricky to accurately choose the right radius with the small slider (despite my little fingers)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Opacity‚Äîopacity of your brush. I reckon it‚Äôs best used at less than 100% to give a more realistic painting effect, the more solid your brush, the more it‚Äôll look like an old-school MS Paint picture!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Type of brush‚ÄîI‚Äôve been sticking with this fine paintbrush style for now. It‚Äôs a very predictable, softish round brush.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Colour palette‚Äîcolour selection that beats Photoshop. It‚Äôd be great to have an interface this good for Photoshop. You can be so specific in your colour choices and easily change by Hue, Saturation or Tone which is great if you‚Äôre creating gentle gradations.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;the-incredible-layers-feature&#34;&gt;The incredible Layers feature&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You can only have five layers, but you can merge your layers together when you‚Äôve used all five to give you more control over editing work on a new layer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In my fish picture, I started with some basic line-drawing and blocking out colour. Then on a layer above, I gave it a wash of light yellow with a big fat, mostly transparent, brush and set that layer to 50%. This made that wash more subtle, then I merged the layer down (I knew I wouldn‚Äôt need to finely edit this rough stuff later) to make my basic base layer.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_3_hu45c99836b4586ed45922367e3010e969_307144_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_3_hu45c99836b4586ed45922367e3010e969_307144_500x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 500w,/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_3_hu45c99836b4586ed45922367e3010e969_307144_800x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 800w,/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/photo_3.png 1024w&#39;
      src=&#39;photo_3.png&#39; alt=&#39;lowest layer of blocked colour&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The next layer I used to add some more fiddly detail and shadow. I kept this separate from the layer below for¬†if I wanted to go back and erase parts without wiping my base layer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;


    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1024&#39; height=&#39;768&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
