&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/autodesk-sketchbook-pro/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòAutodesk SketchBook Pro‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôve been working with a client who wants every external link on their site to open in a new window. They dislike the idea of users leaving their site for somebody else‚Äôs and not being able to find their way back.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I understand their concern. &lt;em&gt;I really do&lt;/em&gt;. It seems like a perfectly rational feeling but there are a few reasons why this generally isn‚Äôt the right thing to do.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;the-back-button-is-the-second-most-used-form-of-navigation&#34;&gt;The Back button is the second most-used form of navigation.&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If a user wants to go back to your site, they can. If you open in a new window or tab, you make the ‚ÄòBack‚Äô button useless. Don‚Äôt treat your users like they‚Äôre idiots that need to be led-around by the nose. (It helps to be helpful, but not patronising!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;2&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;by-opening-a-link-in-a-new-window-youre-not-giving-the-user-any-other-choice&#34;&gt;By opening a link in a new window, you‚Äôre not giving the user any other choice.&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is my personal pet hate. If I want to open a link in another window or tab, I can do so easily by right-clicking the link and selecting that option (and I‚Äôm sure there‚Äôs numerous shortcuts for such behaviour.) However, if you specify that the link &lt;em&gt;must&lt;/em&gt; open in another window, there‚Äôs nothing I can do about it. You shouldn‚Äôt force users into situations that are uncomfortable against their usual browsing patterns. They will end up associating that discomfort with your site.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;3&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;some-users-just-wont-understand-whats-happening&#34;&gt;Some users just won‚Äôt understand what‚Äôs happening.&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As more and more people get cheap access to the internet, there will be more users who have very basic skills, aren‚Äôt wholly computer-literate, but will browse your site anyway! If you‚Äôd never used a computer before, and were presented with a link that opened in a new window, are you sure you‚Äôd understand what just happened? These users may not understand that they‚Äôre now in a new window or tab. They‚Äôll have a great big ‚ÄòBack‚Äô button screaming at them, not a ‚ÄòClose this window or tab and then select the relevant window or tab to view it again‚Äô button.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;4&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;theres-no-guarantee-that-when-the-user-closes-that-window-theyll-go-back-to-your-site&#34;&gt;There‚Äôs no guarantee that, when the user closes that window, they‚Äôll go back to your site.&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If I open a page in a new tab on Safari, it gets added to the end of my list of tabs. If I‚Äôve already got another tab open that has the BBC website in, when I close the new tab, it‚Äôll go back to the BBC website, not your website.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;5&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;its-irritating-for-mobile-browsers&#34;&gt;It‚Äôs irritating for mobile browsers.&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Some mobile browsers may just ignore your ‚ÄòOpen in New Window‚Äô suggestion as they don‚Äôt support multiple windows. If you‚Äôre browsing using Mobile Safari, it will do this very dramatic shrink-this-window open-another-window animation. The back button is much less fiddly. People using mobile browsers are more likely to be on-the-go and less likely to put up with switching windows all the time when browsing your site.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;please-be-considerate-of-your-users-and-dont-treat-them-like-they-dont-know-what-theyre-doing-for-those-that-really-dont-know-what-theyre-doing-keep-it-simple-if-users-remember-yours-as-the-site-that-was-easy-to-use-thats-going-to-make-you-a-lot-more-popular-than-forcing-them-to-look-at-your-content-ever-will&#34;&gt;Please be considerate of your users, and don‚Äôt treat them like they don‚Äôt know what they‚Äôre doing. For those that &lt;em&gt;really&lt;/em&gt; don‚Äôt know what they‚Äôre doing, keep it simple. If users remember yours as the site that was easy to use, that‚Äôs going to make you a lot more popular than forcing them to look at your content ever will.&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Some other handy articles I found on this subject:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.problogdesign.com/blog-usability/new-window-for-a-new-link/&#34;&gt;Should Links Open In A New Window Or Not?‚ÄîPro Blog Design&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.useit.com/alertbox/open_new_windows.html&#34;&gt;Open New Windows for PDF and other Non-Web Documents‚ÄîJakob Nielsen‚Äôs Alertbox&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://dubroy.com/blog/my-chi2010-talk-a-study-of-tabbed-browsing/&#34;&gt;My CHI2010 talk: A Study of Tabbed Browsing‚ÄîPatrick Dubroy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.webnauts.net/new-window.html&#34;&gt;Avoid Forcing To Open In A New Window‚ÄîWebnauts&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.useit.com/alertbox/990530.html&#34;&gt;The Top Ten Web Design Mistakes of 1999‚ÄîJakob Nielsen‚Äôs Alertbox&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://robertnyman.com/2006/02/13/how-evil-is-the-target-attribute/&#34;&gt;How Evil Is The Target Attribute?‚ÄîRobert‚Äôs Talk&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
