&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://laurakalbag.com/open-in-a-new-window/&#34;&gt;Read the original post, ‚ÄòOpen In A New Window‚Äô&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Since I started using &lt;a href=&#34;http://zootool.com/&#34; title=&#34;Zootool&#34;&gt;Zootool&lt;/a&gt; in March I‚Äôve been totally addicted.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I‚Äôd been looking for a scrapbook-style app, to stash all the inspiration I find, for a while. On cool sites like &lt;a href=&#34;http://dribbble.com/&#34;&gt;Dribbble&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.drawar.com/&#34;&gt;Drawar&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;http://ffffound.com/&#34;&gt;FFFFound&lt;/a&gt; and all over the web, I‚Äôm always finding pretty things I‚Äôd like to keep and use when I‚Äôm designing later on.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I was trying to do this with &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.realmacsoftware.com/littlesnapper/&#34; title=&#34;Little Snapper screen capture software&#34;&gt;Little Snapper&lt;/a&gt; but found, whilst it‚Äôs great for posh and annotated screenshots, it wasn‚Äôt quick enough to capture and file the images and sites that I‚Äôd found. Previously I‚Äôd also tried &lt;a href=&#34;http://flickr.com&#34;&gt;Flickr&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;http://skitch.com/&#34;&gt;Skitch&lt;/a&gt; and even just saving image files in a folder on my hard drive. All were a nightmare to maintain and find the images after I‚Äôd stored them. Then a little ad with a pretty rhino popped up in Tweetie‚Äôs &lt;a href=&#34;http://fusionads.net/&#34;&gt;Fusion ads&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;#asterisk&#34;&gt;*&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Zootool captured me from the beginning with the mac-like, slick and incredibly useful interface. The lovely woodiness doesn‚Äôt look tacky, all the buttons and form elements work exactly as you expect. And it is unbelievably quick to capture an image, video, page or document using the bookmarklets provided¬†and then get back to what you‚Äôre doing.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1180&#39; height=&#39;697&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/zootool-the-best-and-most-beautiful-tool-for-storing-inspiration/Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24_hu31b81140ee96ea1039e30bc8139c9d11_736637_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/zootool-the-best-and-most-beautiful-tool-for-storing-inspiration/Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24_hu31b81140ee96ea1039e30bc8139c9d11_736637_500x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 500w,/zootool-the-best-and-most-beautiful-tool-for-storing-inspiration/Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24_hu31b81140ee96ea1039e30bc8139c9d11_736637_800x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 800w,/zootool-the-best-and-most-beautiful-tool-for-storing-inspiration/Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24.png 1180w&#39;
      src=&#39;Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24.png&#39; alt=&#39;my Zootool Zoo&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And once you‚Äôve got a cool collection of images in your cutely named ‚ÄòZoo‚Äô, you can browse by category, tag or just search to find them again. All in an interface that feels like a desktop app but in-browser.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It‚Äôs not really restricted to scrapbook-style use either. I was surprised to find that other people use it for just saving funny videos (my tunnel vision just saw how perfect it was for saving lovely pictures and thought everyone would use it for that) and you can import all your Delicious bookmarks to use it as a visual bookmark browser.&lt;/p&gt;



    &lt;img
      class=&#39;landscape&#39;
      width=&#39;1180&#39; height=&#39;697&#39;
      sizes=&#39;(min-width: 1380px) 750px, (min-width: 820px) 719px, (min-width: 740px) calc(-33.33vw &amp;#43; 875px), (min-width: 340px) calc(92.63vw - 39px), calc(100vw - 32px)&#39;
      srcset=&#39;https://laurakalbag.com/zootool-the-best-and-most-beautiful-tool-for-storing-inspiration/Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24_hu31b81140ee96ea1039e30bc8139c9d11_736637_300x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 300w,/zootool-the-best-and-most-beautiful-tool-for-storing-inspiration/Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24_hu31b81140ee96ea1039e30bc8139c9d11_736637_500x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 500w,/zootool-the-best-and-most-beautiful-tool-for-storing-inspiration/Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24_hu31b81140ee96ea1039e30bc8139c9d11_736637_800x0_resize_mitchellnetravali_2.png 800w,/zootool-the-best-and-most-beautiful-tool-for-storing-inspiration/Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24.png 1180w&#39;
      src=&#39;Screen-shot-2010-06-10-at-20.46.24.png&#39; alt=&#39;my Zootool Zoo&#39;
    /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The amount of tags can feel restrictive, as it‚Äôs only ten per item, but then again I‚Äôm a taxonomy addict. I‚Äôve started using a tag of @origin (@dribbble, @ffffound, @twitter) as well to make sure I remember where I found the image or site in the first place in case I need to give proper attribution.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Zootool also has special versions for iPhone and iPad (though for some reason I can‚Äôt scroll on the iPad version,) where native mac-ness of the design is really clear, there‚Äôs a Flickr-style badge that‚Äôs perfect for a blog (see below!) and you can even also use Fluid app to pretend it‚Äôs a real desktop app whenever you‚Äôre connected to the internet. I use Fluid with the MobileMe Olive theme that looks lovely against the Zootool design.&lt;/p&gt;



